100	18402	Would you believe anyone who told you that the one thing that could save you time, money, and calories was a burger?\r\n\r\nProbably notespecially if that burger also happened not to include any meat. But once your apartment fills with the aroma of these hearty, healthy, flavorful burgers, the truth cant be denied. You really can knock out three New Years Resolutions at once, all thanks to a little quinoa and black beans.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7351" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers-7/" rel="attachment wp-att-7351"><img class="size-full wp-image-7351" alt="Photo by Sally Zhang" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/Crispy-Quinoa-Black-Bean-Burgers-7.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Sally Zhang[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7345" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/" rel="attachment wp-att-7345"><img class="size-full wp-image-7345" alt="Photo by Sally Zhang" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/Crispy-Quinoa-Black-Bean-Burgers.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Sally Zhang[/caption]\r\n\r\nBy now were all probably tired of hearing about the amazing quinoa, but its virtues are worth rehashing: its simple to cook in large volumes and save for later, it can be incorporated into endless recipes, and not to mention, its an incredibly healthy (and gluten-free!) way to get in your grains, fiber, minerals and protein. Its also perfect for vegetarians or those trying to cut back on meat. Paired with black beans and chopped veggies, each patty takes on a satisfying crispy texture thats a welcome break from typical quinoa salad concoctions and might even turn you off from hamburgers for good.\r\n\r\nThis recipe makes about 5 servings, which you can freeze and reheat later for a quick healthy dinner. Or, scramble up the leftover mixture and use as a meat substitute in any number of recipes.\r\n\r\n[advanced]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep time: </b>20 minutes\r\n<b>Cook time: </b>25 minutes\r\n<b>Total time: </b>45 minutes\r\n\r\n<b>Servings: </b>Approximately 5 burgers\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients:</b>\r\n1 cup quinoa, uncooked\r\n2 cups water\r\n1 15 oz. can black beans, drained\r\n2 tablespoons finely chopped red onion\r\n2 tablespoons slivered red onion\r\n cup finely chopped carrots\r\n1 clove garlic, minced\r\n cup whole wheat breadcrumbs\r\n tablespoon paprika\r\n teaspoon salt\r\n1 egg\r\n3 tablespoons olive oil\r\n2 slices bread\r\n2 tablespoons hummus or other condiments\r\nLettuce, tomatoes, etc. for topping\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Using a colander with the finest holes you can find, rinse quinoa to remove the bitter outer coating or saponins from the grains.\r\n\r\n2. Bring quinoa and water to a boil over high heat, then reduce heat and simmer for 15 minutes until water is mostly absorbed and quinoa is cooked. Fluff quinoa with a fork.\r\n\r\n3. While quinoa cooks, chop onions and carrots, and mince garlic.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7346" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers-2/" rel="attachment wp-att-7346"><img class="size-full wp-image-7346" alt="Photo by Sally Zhang" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/Crispy-Quinoa-Black-Bean-Burgers-2.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Sally Zhang[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7348" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers-4/" rel="attachment wp-att-7348"><img class="size-full wp-image-7348" alt="Photo by Sally Zhang" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/Crispy-Quinoa-Black-Bean-Burgers-4.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Sally Zhang[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Heat slivered red onion in a small pan over medium heat. Drizzle with olive oil, sprinkle with salt, and cook until caramelized, or about 15 minutes, tossing occasionally.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7349" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers-5/" rel="attachment wp-att-7349"><img class="size-full wp-image-7349" alt="Photo by Sally Zhang" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/Crispy-Quinoa-Black-Bean-Burgers-5.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Sally Zhang[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Mash black beans with a fork until a slightly chunky paste forms.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7352" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers-8/" rel="attachment wp-att-7352"><img class="size-full wp-image-7352" alt="Photo by Sally Zhang" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/Crispy-Quinoa-Black-Bean-Burgers-8.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Sally Zhang[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Mix cooked quinoa, mashed beans, chopped raw onion, carrots, garlic, breadcrumbs, and seasoning in a large bowl. Mix in egg.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7353" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers-9/" rel="attachment wp-att-7353"><img class="size-full wp-image-7353" alt="Photo by Sally Zhang" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/Crispy-Quinoa-Black-Bean-Burgers-9.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Sally Zhang[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Heat olive oil in a large skillet while forming mixture into patties. Once oil is hot, place patties in pan and cook until crispy, or about 5 minutes on each side.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7354" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers-10/" rel="attachment wp-att-7354"><img class="size-full wp-image-7354" alt="Photo by Sally Zhang" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/Crispy-Quinoa-Black-Bean-Burgers-10.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Sally Zhang[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. Spread hummus or other condiments on toasted bread. Top with burgers and caramelized onions, as well as fresh greens and any other toppings. Enjoy!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7358" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burgers-14/" rel="attachment wp-att-7358"><img class="size-full wp-image-7358" alt="Photo by Sally Zhang" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/Crispy-Quinoa-Black-Bean-Burgers-14.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Sally Zhang[/caption]	Crispy Quinoa Black Bean Burger	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/crispy-quinoa-black-bean-burger/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:29.143381	2014-01-14 18:55:29.143381	:</b>\r\n1 cup quinoa, uncooked\r\n2 cups water\r\n1 15 oz. can black beans, drained\r\n2 tablespoons finely chopped red onion\r\n2 tablespoons slivered red onion\r\n cup finely chopped carrots\r\n1 clove garlic, minced\r\n cup whole wheat breadcrumbs\r\n tablespoon paprika\r\n teaspoon salt\r\n1 egg\r\n3 tablespoons olive oil\r\n2 slices bread\r\n2 tablespoons hummus or other condiments\r\nLettuce, tomatoes, etc. for topping\r\n\r\n<strong>
101	18404	Ina Garten, the Barefoot Contessa, is a pioneer in the art of simple entertainment and an inspiration to middle-aged women across the nation. This became blaringly obvious as I stood for hours with 800 other people at Old Orchard Mall waiting to get this amazing chefs signature in a copy of her new cookbook Foolproof. People in line couldnt say enough about how much they love her easy entertaining tips for cocktails and dinner parties. Still others raved about her tried and true recipes that have never failed them.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7226" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/an-ode-to-ina/dsc_0461-4/" rel="attachment wp-att-7226"><img class="size-full wp-image-7226" alt="Photo by Maddy Shannon." src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/12/DSC_0461.jpg" width="1024" height="1234" /></a> Photo by Maddy Shannon.[/caption]\r\n\r\nHer food network show Barefoot Contessa typically features Ina cooking a multi-course meal for her adorable husband Jeffrey and friends. While the interactions on her show are hilariously staged, there is no doubt that she will always provide viewers with some awesome time and energy-saving tips, and definitely some drool-worthy food. She credits Eli Zabar with her motto: "All you have to do is cook to enhance the ingredients."<a title="" href="#_ftn1">[1]</a>\r\n\r\nIna is not a trained chef, so her recipes are really tailored towards people with limited cooking experience  it is actually difficult to make an Ina Garten recipe poorly. That's why I was shocked by the homogenouscrowd of mothers at her book signing. Ina takes away all the difficulty of cooking and entertaining and replaces it with minimalism and simple, quality ingredients. If theres one thing college students strive for, it's just that  to minimize effort and still maintain quality.\r\n\r\nSo in an ode to Inas new cookbook Foolproof, I took her tomato topping from her Salmon &amp; Melting Cherry Tomatoes recipe and put it on the garlic toasts from her recipe for Winter Minestrone &amp; Garlic Bruschetta (because why not mix and match recipes?). And guess what? It was delicious!\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep time:</strong> 10 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook time:</strong> 30 minutes\r\n<strong>Total time:</strong> 40 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> About 10 pieces of bruschetta\r\n\r\n<strong>Garlic Bruschetta</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 baguette\r\nGood olive oil\r\n1 garlic clove, cut in half\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Preheat the oven to 425F.\r\n2. Slice the baguette at a 45 degree angle into  inch-thick slices.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7216" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/an-ode-to-ina/dsc_0467/" rel="attachment wp-att-7216"><img class="size-full wp-image-7216" alt="Photo by Maddy Shannon." src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/12/DSC_0467.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maddy Shannon.[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Brush both sides of the bread with olive oil and bake on a sheet pan for about 6 minutes until lightly toasted.\r\n4. Take the slices out of the oven and rub the surface of each one with the cut side of a garlic clove half.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7217" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/an-ode-to-ina/dsc_0482/" rel="attachment wp-att-7217"><img class="size-full wp-image-7217" alt="Photo by Maddy Shannon." src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/12/DSC_0482.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maddy Shannon.[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>Tomato Topping</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\nGood olive oil\r\n1 cup chopped sweet onion\r\n2 teaspoons minced garlic (2 cloves)\r\n2 cups (1 pint) cherry or grape tomatoes, halved through the stem (vertically)\r\n1 tablespoons good balsamic vinegar\r\n1 tablespoons julienned fresh basil leave