e</li>\r\n\t<li>lightest vegetables at the top.</li>\r\n\t<li>Drizzle with any remaining marinade, fold foil into a tent pack (see sidebar on previous page) and place on hot coals of the fire.</li>\r\n\t<li>Cook until meat is browned and veggies are softened, about 2030 minutes. If you are using an oven, bake at 350F for 2025 minutes.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>TIP:</strong> To make this dish vegetarian, leave out the meat and double the mushrooms.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_13106" align="alignleft" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-13106" alt="By Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/11_pineapple.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> By Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>Pineapple Upside-Down Cake</strong>\r\n\r\n[freshman]\r\n\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 10-12 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 or 2 pineapple rings (canned or fresh)\r\n1 cake doughnut\r\n1 tablespoon butter, softened\r\n1 tablespoon brown sugar\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Mix butter and brown sugar in a small bowl until combined.</li>\r\n\t<li>Place cake doughnut in the center of a sheet of tin foil. Spread butter and sugar mixture on top of doughnut.</li>\r\n\t<li>Layer pineapple ring(s) on top of buttered doughnut and fold up in a flat pack.</li>\r\n\t<li>Cook on hot coals until butter has melted and pineapple is soft and slightly caramelized, about 57 minutes. If you are using an oven, bake at 350F for about 5 minutes.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div style="width: 50%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: 1px;">\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Wrap It Up In Tin Foil</strong>\r\nIllustrations by Kyle Hancher.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">A well-constructed foil pack is the first step toward achieving optimum goodness for your tin-foil dinner. For basic, all-over browning (as when cooking veggies and/or potatoes) youll want to make a flat pack .</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><