ge-9133" alt="Photo by Alex Tom" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/02/Combining-Ingredients-to-Toast.jpg" width="1024" height="684" /> Photo by Alex Tom[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Add cinnamon and salt and stir everything together to coat.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_9148" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-9148" alt="Photo by Alex Tom" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/02/Mixing-Ingredients-Before-Toasting.jpg" width="1024" height="684" /> Photo by Alex Tom[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Place baking sheet in the oven and bake for 10 minutes, stirring frequently (every 3-4 minutes) to prevent burning at the edges.\r\n5. Meanwhile, mash bananas with a fork.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_9143" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-9143" alt="Photo by Alex Tom" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/02/Mashing-Bananas.jpg" width="1024" height="684" /> Photo by Alex Tom[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. In a small saucepan over medium-low heat, combine the mashed bananas, nut butter, vanilla and agave or honey. Stir mixture for a few minutes until it is fully combined and warm, about 5 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_9144" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-9144" alt="Photo by Alex Tom" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/02/Ingredients-in-Saucepan.jpg" width="1024" height="684" /> Photo by Alex Tom[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. In a large bowl combine the banana mixture with the toasted oats and nuts.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_9149" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-9149" alt="Photo by Alex Tom" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/02/Mixing-All-Ingredients.jpg" width="1024" height="684" /> Photo by Alex Tom[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Stir in the dried fruit. If you are using larger pieces of fruit, such as dried apricots, cut them into smaller pieces about the size of raisins.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_9134" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-9134" alt="Photo by Alex Tom" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/02/Cutting-Apricots-2.jpg" width="1024" height="684" /> Photo by Alex Tom[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Leave an inch hanging over each side of the pan to use as handles for easy removal of the bars after baking.\r\n\r\n<strong>Tip:</strong> The size of the baking sheet will determine how thick your bars turn out. If you want thicker, chewier bars a smaller pan will work better. However, dont pick a pan smaller than 8x8. For thinner bars, a shallow cookie sheet with 1 inch sides works great.\r\n\r\n9. Pour the mixture into the pan. Use a spatula to spread out and flatten the mixture evenly. Dont worry if the mixture doesnt reach every end of the pan, especially if you're using a large cookie sheet.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_9151" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-9151" alt="Photo by Alex Tom" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/02/Pouring-Ingredients-in-Pan.jpg" width="1024" height="684" /> Photo by Alex Tom[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_9150" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-9150" alt="Photo by Alex Tom" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/02/Patting-Down-Ingredients.jpg" width="1024" height="684" /> Photo by Alex Tom[/caption]\r\n\r\n10. Bake for 25 minutes, or until the edges begin to brown.\r\n11. Let cool then place pan in the refrigerator for 30 minutes.\r\n12. Remove the bars from the pan using the parchment handles. Use a sharp knife to cut out individual bars. The size of the bars is up to you!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_9140" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-9140" alt="Photo by Alex Tom" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content