82	17888	After visiting Prague for spring break, I learned a lot about the cuisine. Czech diet 101: the Czech diet consists mostly of meat, potatoes, cabbage and cheese. One of their delicacies is this fried cheese sandwich with garlicky herb and lemon mayonnaise.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_869" align="aligncenter" width="682"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/1-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-869" alt="Photo by Heather Harris" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/1-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris-682x1024.jpg" width="682" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Heather Harris[/caption]\r\n\r\nThis delicious dish is commonly sold on street carts and is a cultural staple. If you ask me, street food is the best way to get a feel for a neighborhood's attitude towards food, and this fried cheese sandwich with savory mayo brought me to a happy place. So, I wanted to bring to you all the same happinessyou can make this sandwich from the comfort of your own home!\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep Time</b>: 25 minutes\r\n<b>Cook Time</b>: 5 minutes\r\n<b>Total time</b>: 30 minutes\r\n\r\n<b>Servings</b>: 2\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_870" align="aligncenter" width="717"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/2-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-870" alt="Photo by Heather Harris" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/2-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris-717x1024.jpg" width="717" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Heather Harris[/caption]\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients</b>:\r\n\r\n<b>Amped up Mayo\r\n</b>A few shakes of fennel seed (very potent flavor, use sparingly)\r\n teaspoon fresh thyme\r\n5 fresh basil leaves, chopped\r\n1 tablespoon of lemon zest\r\nJuice from lemon\r\n garlic clove, finely chopped\r\n4 tablespoons mayonnaise\r\nSalt and pepper, to taste\r\n\r\n<b>Gooey Fried Cheese\r\n</b>1 small mozzarella cut into 1/2 inch slices\r\n3/4 cup oil\r\ncup flour\r\n2 eggs\r\n3/4 cup plain breadcrumb\r\n1 tablespoon Parmesan cheese\r\nHerbs de Province\r\nSalt and pepper, to taste\r\n2 buns (any, but a Kaiser Roll with sesame seeds is most traditional)\r\n\r\n<b>Directions</b>:\r\n1. In a bowl combine the fennel seed, thyme, basil, chopped garlic, lemon zest and juice and mayo. Add salt and pepper to taste, and set aside.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_873" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/MAYO-MIX-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-873" alt="Photo by Heather Harris" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/MAYO-MIX-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris-1024x618.jpg" width="1024" height="618" /></a> Photo by Heather Harris[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Whisk together two eggs in a bowl, and place flour and breadcrumb in their own bowls.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_871" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/breadcrumb-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-871" alt="Photo by Heather Harris" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/breadcrumb-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris-1024x682.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Heather Harris[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. To the breadcrumbs, add the Parmesan cheese, salt, pepper and herbs de Province, or any substitution discussed in my previous article <a title="3 Ways to Upgrade Your Movie Snack" href="http://nyuspoon.com/3-ways-to-upgrade-your-movie-snack/" target="_blank">3 Ways to Upgrade Your Movie Snack</a>. If you really dont want to do this at all you can always buy pre-seasoned breadcrumbs.\r\n4. Add oil to a frying pan and heat over medium heat.\r\n5. Dip mozzarella slices in flour, then egg and finally breadcrumbs.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_875" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Mozzarella-in-breadcrumb-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-875" alt="Photo by Heather Harris" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/Mozzarella-in-breadcrumb-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris-1024x718.jpg" width="1024" height="718" /></a> Photo by Heather Harris[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Place mozzarella slices in pan. Cook each side about 2 minutes, or until golden brown. This should take no more than 5 minutes total.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_872" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/fried-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-872" alt="Photo by Heather Harris" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/fried-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris-1024x682.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Heather Harris[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Place mozzarella on plate with a paper towel to drain excess oil.\r\n8. Slice and toast buns.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_881" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/HeatherHarris-EatAbroadatHome-016.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-881" alt="Photo by Heather Harris" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/HeatherHarris-EatAbroadatHome-016-1024x682.jpg" width="1024" height="682" /></a> Photo by Heather Harris[/caption]\r\n\r\n9. Generously coat the top and bottom of each bun with the flavored mayo from beforetrust me, be generous. Place 2 slices of fried mozzarella on each bottom bun. Top with fresh basil leaves and cover with other bun.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_874" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/mayo-on-bread-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-874" alt="Photo by Heather Harris" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/mayo-on-bread-Eat-abroad-at-home-Heather-Harris-1024x678.jpg" width="1024" height="678" /></a> Photo by Heather Harris[/caption]\r\n\r\n10. Enjoy the lemony, gooey, crunchy masterpiece that is this sandwich.	Fried Cheese Sandwich with Garlicky Herb and Lemon Mayo	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/bring-prague-to-your-kitchen/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:28.88952	2014-01-14 18:55:28.88952	</b>:\r\n\r\n<b>Amped up Mayo\r\n</b>A few shakes of fennel seed (very potent flavor, use sparingly)\r\n teaspoon fresh thyme\r\n5 fresh basil leaves, chopped\r\n1 tablespoon of lemon zest\r\nJuice from lemon\r\n garlic clove, finely chopped\r\n4 tablespoons mayonnaise\r\nSalt and pepper, to taste\r\n\r\n<b>Gooey Fried Cheese\r\n</b>1 small mozzarella cut into 1/2 inch slices\r\n3/4 cup oil\r\ncup flour\r\n2 eggs\r\n3/4 cup plain breadcrumb\r\n1 tablespoon Parmesan cheese\r\nHerbs de Province\r\nSalt and pepper, to taste\r\n2 buns (any, but a Kaiser Roll with sesame seeds is most traditional)\r\n\r\n<b>
83	17899	Get cozy with this nest for Sunday brunch! Many of us eat eggs and toast for breakfast, but the routine can get a little dull. Jazz up your morning munch with ham,mayonnaiseand some oven-happy-time. For special occasions, like Mother's day, you can use a heart shaped cookie cutter.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time</strong>: 5 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time</strong>: 20 minutes\r\n<strong>Total time</strong>: 25 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings</strong>: 1\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_913" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/ingredients-Version-2.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-913" alt="Photo by Lily Chin" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/ingredients-Version-2-1024x681.jpg" width="1024" height="681" /></a> Photo by Lily Chin[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>:\r\n2 slices of bread\r\n1 egg\r\n2 slices of ham\r\n2 tablespoons mayonnaise\r\nSalt &amp; pepper to taste\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions</strong>:\r\n1. Preheat oven to300F.\r\n2. Use a cookie cutter or knife to cut a hole in one slice of bread, yielding enough space for an egg.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_932" align="alignnone" width="685"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/direction1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-932" alt="Photo by Lily Chin" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/04/direction1-685x1024.jpg" width="685" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Lily Chin[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Place a slice of ham on the other slice of bread.\r\n4. Spread mayonnaise near the edges of the cut bread.*\r\n5. Press the cut bread, mayonnaise side down, on top of the ham bread.\r\n6. Spread mayonnaise on top of the cut bread to cover completely. **\r\n7. Cut the ham into small pieces, place on to the corners of the cut bread.\r\n8. Crack an egg into the hole.\r\n9. Season with salt &amp; pepper.\r\n10. Bake for 20 minutes.\r\n\r\n<strong>Notes</strong>:\r\n*The mayonnaise creates a seal between the ham and the top bread, so raw egg doesnt seep out when the bread is cooking.\r\n**The mayonnaise on top of the cut bread prevents burning. If patches of bread become exposed, those areas will burn.\r\n***This cooking time yields a bright yellow soft yolk, almost done. For runny or solid yolk, decrease or increase cooking time by 4 minutes.	Ham & Egg in a Nest	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/ham-egg-in-a-nest/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:28.903936	2014-01-14 18:55:28.903936	</strong>:\r\n2 slices of bread\r\n1 egg\r\n2 slices of ham\r\n2 tablespoons mayonnaise\r\nSalt &amp; pepper to taste\r\n\r\n<strong>
