88	18152	Sometimes, you just can't make a pie. Actually, most of the time you can't make a pie. It simply isn't feasible in campus dorms or small, food-processor-lacking apartment kitchens. They're too laborious to make, are difficult to sell at bake sales and will likely elicit some judgment if you bust some out during a late night library session. Still, just because you can't make an apple pie doesn't mean you can't get your baked goods fix. These bars have a generous apple-to-batter ratio, ensuring each bite is full of that buttery dough and apple flavor combo that makes the classic apple pie so popular. Even better, they only require one bowl and one pan to make. Once they're cool, you can enjoy these treats immediately or pack them away for a sweet snack later on.\r\n\r\n[sophomore]\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings: </strong>20 bars\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 20 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong> 45-50 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 1 hour and 5-10 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n2 sticks unsalted butter\r\n1 2/3 cup sugar\r\n2 eggs\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla\r\n3 small apples, peeled, cored and chopped\r\n1/2 cup chopped walnuts\r\n2 cups all-purpose flour\r\n2 teaspoons cinnamon\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n1 teaspoon baking powder\r\n1/2 teaspoon salt\r\n\r\n<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/apple-walnut-bars/olympus-digital-camera-80/" rel="attachment wp-att-7795"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-7795" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/P10176482-1024x768.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Preheat oven to 350F.\r\n2. Melt butter in a microwave-safe bowl.\r\n3. In a large bowl, whisk together butter, sugar, eggs and vanilla.\r\n4. In a separate mixing bowl, whisk together flour, cinnamon, baking soda, baking powder and salt. Add this dry mixture to the melted butter mixture and stir to incorporate.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7658" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/apple-walnut-bars/olympus-digital-camera-70/" rel="attachment wp-att-7658"><img class="size-large wp-image-7658" alt="Photo by Kendra Valkema" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/P1017688-1024x768.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Kendra Valkema[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Mix in apple chunks and walnuts.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7660" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/apple-walnut-bars/olympus-digital-camera-72/" rel="attachment wp-att-7660"><img class="size-large wp-image-7660" alt="Photo by Kendra Valkema" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/P1017705-1024x768.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Kendra Valkema[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Pour the batter in a 9x13 baking pan that has been greased and floured. See <a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/lazy-morning-banana-cake/" target="_blank">this post</a> on how to grease and flour a baking pan (steps 2-4). It's a great method to make any pan non-stick.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_7661" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/apple-walnut-bars/olympus-digital-camera-73/" rel="attachment wp-att-7661"><img class="size-large wp-image-7661" alt="Photo by Kendra Valkema" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/01/P1017717-1024x768.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Kendra Valkema[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Bake for 45-50 minutes, or until the top has cracked and a toothpick inserted into the center of the pan comes out with just a few crumbs.\r\n8. Cool completely before cutting into bars.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/apple-walnut-bars/olympus-digital-camera-77/" rel="attachment wp-att-7789"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-7789" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2