162	19538	We all know how much college students rely on that late night pizza whether it's for getting through that last essay, weekend drunchies or just a casual night with friends. Although delivery pizza may sound tempting, you can save a few bucks (and calories) by making your own healthy, personal pizza with just a toaster oven.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time: </strong>5minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong>10 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong>15 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong>1\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 whole wheat flatbread\r\n1/2 cup pizza sauce\r\n1 1/2 cup broccoli, chopped into florets\r\n3/4 cup shredded cheese\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Microwave broccoli florets for 30 seconds so they are soft. Set aside.<strong></strong>\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="819"]<a title="P9270002 by spoonuniversity, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/100601615@N07/10032386475/"><img alt="P9270002" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3667/10032386475_3573ee6a53_b.jpg" width="819" height="717" /></a> Photo by Emily Hu[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Spread pizza sauce evenly on flatbread, leaving a 1-inch border for crust.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="738"]<a title="Untitled by spoonuniversity, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/100601615@N07/10032096803/"><img class=" " alt="Untitled" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5531/10032096803_dc33d3a44b_b.jpg" width="738" height="553" /></a> Photo by Emily Hu[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Sprinkle broccoli and cheese evenly on the sauce area of the pizza.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a title="Untitled by spoonuniversity, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/100601615@N07/10032091523/"><img alt="Untitled" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7392/10032091523_a3bf492735_b.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Emily Hu[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Heat in toaster oven at 375<b></b>F on the "toast" setting for 10 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="768"]<a title="Untitled by spoonuniversity, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/100601615@N07/10031957484/"><img alt="Untitled" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5537/10031957484_c1712eca1a_b.jpg" width="768" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Emily Hu[/caption]	Easy Flatbread Pizza	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/?p=19538	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:29.793076	2014-01-14 18:55:29.793076	:</strong>\r\n1 whole wheat flatbread\r\n1/2 cup pizza sauce\r\n1 1/2 cup broccoli, chopped into florets\r\n3/4 cup shredded cheese\r\n\r\n<strong>
163	19580	Healthy snacks are hard to come by on college campuses, which is why it's great that it is so darn easy to make them yourself. Another plus: these taste similar to the beloved Chewy Bars from your childhood, but are significantly better for you. Even better? You can customize them to include exactly what you want, so feel free to substitute ingredients to include your favorites. These bars are portable, inexpensive, quick, and easy to make (in the microwave!), and delicious. Enjoy!\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong>10 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time: </strong>30 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong>40 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong>8\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 stick butter, softened\r\n1/4 cup honey\r\n1/4 cup packed brown sugar\r\n1/4 cup peanut butter\r\n2 cups quick cooking oats (not rolled oats!)\r\n1 cup crispy rice cereal\r\n1/2 teaspoon vanilla\r\n2-3 tablespoons mini chocolate chips\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_19588" align="alignnone" width="715"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3932-1022x1024.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-19588" alt="IMG_3932-1022x1024" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3932-1022x1024.jpg" width="715" height="717" /></a> Photo by Rachel Conners[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. In a large bowl, stir together quick cooking oats and crispy rice cereal. Set aside.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_19589" align="alignnone" width="686"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3935-1024x684.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-19589" alt="IMG_3935-1024x684" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3935-1024x684.jpg" width="686" height="458" /></a> Photo by Rachel Conners[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. In a heatproof bowl or Pyrex measuring cup, stir together butter, honey and brown sugar. Microwave until it starts boiling (about 2 minutes with my low-wattage microwave, could be sooner for you). Once it begins to boil, let boil for 1 more minute in the microwave. Remove from microwave and stir in peanut butter and vanilla until smooth.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_19591" align="alignnone" width="717"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3943-1024x6821.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-19591" alt="IMG_3943-1024x682" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3943-1024x6821.jpg" width="717" height="477" /></a> Photo by Rachel Conners[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_19582" align="alignnone" width="717"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3945-1024x680.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-19582" alt="IMG_3945-1024x680" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3945-1024x680.jpg" width="717" height="476" /></a> Photo by Rachel Conners[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Pour hot honey mixture over dry ingredients and mix until all the dry ingredients are coated.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_19583" align="alignnone" width="717"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3950-1024x681.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-19583" alt="IMG_3950-1024x681" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3950-1024x681.jpg" width="717" height="477" /></a> Photo by Rachel Conners[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_19584" align="alignnone" width="717"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3954-1024x682.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-19584" alt="IMG_3954-1024x682" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IMG_3954-1024x682.jpg" width="717" height="477" /></a> Photo by Rachel Conners[/caption]\r\n\r\n4.Pour into a lightly greased 8x8 pan. Press the mixture firmly into the pan and sprinkle the chocolate chips on top. Let sit at room temperature for about 2 hours or in the refrigerator for a half hour or until set.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_19586" align="alignnone" width="717"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-c