65.png" width="993" height="660" /></a>7. Serve and garnish with chopped cilantro and basil, if desired.
179	19742	When you think of the classics, spaghetti with tomato sauce is definitely up there. Its one of those meals that never gets old and has been popular since before any of us can remember. Some of the more trendy and current food fads are definitely fun to indulge in (who doesnt have a soft spot for cupcakes and Froyo?), but there is something to be said for perfecting the recipe for a dish as timeless as tomato sauce. Its one of those things that even an amateur cook, like myself, should at least attempt to add to their repertoire. Although this recipe is a bit of a commitment, there is a lot of down time while the tomatoes cook that you can use to prepare other parts of your mealor lets be honest, you can totally do homework during that time. There's nothing too technical about this sauce and the simple and fresh ingredients practically ensure that youll end up with something delicious!\r\n\r\n<em>Adapted from Smitten Kitchen</em><em></em>\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time: </strong>20 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time: </strong>50 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time: </strong>1 hour 10 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings: </strong>4 small portions\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n3 pounds of plum tomatoes (look for oval shaped tomatoes)\r\n3/4 teaspoons salt\r\n1 large clove of garlic, thinly sliced (a clove is one segment of a head of garlic)\r\nA pinch of red pepper flakes\r\nA small handful of basil leaves, most left whole, a few slivered for garnish\r\n1/4 cup olive oil\r\n12 ounces (3/4 pound) spaghetti\r\n1 tablespoon unsalted butter (optional)\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Bring a large pot of water to a boil.\r\n2. Cut a small X at the bottom of each tomato (this will help with peeling the tomatoes later).\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3331" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture9.png"><img class="size-large wp-image-3331" title="screen-capture" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture9-1024x649.png" width="1024" height="649" /></a> Photo by Alia Wilhelm[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Blanch the tomatoes in the boiling water for 10 to 30 seconds, then either rinse them under cold water or shock them in an ice water bath. They should now be very easy to peel.\r\n4. Peel the tomatoes by hand and discard the skin. Keep the pot full of hot water; you can use it to cook your spaghetti in later.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3332" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-18.png"><img class="size-large wp-image-3332" title="screen-capture-1" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-18-1024x679.png" width="1024" height="679" /></a> Photo by Alia Wilhelm[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Cut each tomato in half lengthwise and remove the seeds with your fingertips into a small strainer set over a bowl. You can toss the seeds, but keep the juices to add to the sauce later.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3333" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-39.png"><img class="size-large wp-image-3333" title="screen-capture-3" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-39-1024x677.png" width="1024" height="677" /></a> Photo by Alia Wilhelm[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Add the halved tomatoes and salt to a large saucepan and turn the stove to medium-high. You will be adding the pasta to this later so make sure the pan is big enough\r\n\r\n7. Once in the pan, break the tomatoes down. You can use your hands, a knife, or another tool like a potato masher. The more you break down the tomatoes, the smoother your sauce will be. Leave more whole pieces if you prefer a chunkier sauce.\r\n\r\n8. Once the sauce has begun to boil, turn down the heat to medium-low and gently simmer the tomatoes for 35 to 45 minutes, mashing them more if needed. If they begin to look a little dry you can add some of the strained tomato juices you reserved.\r\n\r\n9. While the sauce is cooking, combine the sliced garlic, a few whole basil leaves, a pinch of red pepper flakes and 1/4 cup olive oil in a small saucepan. Heat them slowly over the lowest heat so they take a long time to come to a simmer. Once it does simmer, immediately remove it from the heat and strain the oil into a small dish. Youll need it shortly.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3334" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-27.png"><img class="size-large wp-image-3334" title="screen-capture-2" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-27-1024x607.png" width="1024" height="607" /></a> Photo by Alia Wilhelm[/caption]\r\n\r\n10. When the tomato sauce has been simmering for about 25 minutes (out of 35 to 45), bring your tomato-blanching pot of water back to a boil with some salt. Once it begins to boil rapidly, cook your spaghetti until it is al dente. It should feel like it could use another minute of cooking time. Reserve a half-cup of pasta cooking water and drain the rest. Adding pasta water to sauce helps thicken it because of the starch content of the water.\r\n\r\n11. Once your sauce is cooked to the consistency you like, stir in the reserved olive oil and adjust seasonings to taste. You can add basil, salt, red pepper flakes or whatever you please.\r\n\r\n12. Add drained spaghetti and half the reserved pasta water to the simmering tomato sauce and cook them together for another minute or two. You can add the remaining pasta water if needed to loosen the sauce.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3336" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-47.png"><img class="size-large wp-image-3336" title="screen-capture-4" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-47-1024x679.png" width="1024" height="679" /></a> Photo by Alia Wilhelm[/caption]\r\n\r\n13. If you decide to use the butter, stir it into the sauce.\r\n14. Garnish with some slivered basil and serve immediately.\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;	Simple Homemade Tomato Sauce	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/simple-homemade-tomato-sauce/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:29.954556	2014-01-14 18:55:29.954556	:</strong>\r\n3 pounds of plum tomatoes (look for oval shaped tomatoes)\r\n3/4 teaspoons salt\r\n1 large clove of garlic, thinly sliced (a clove is one segment of a head of garlic)\r\nA pinch of red pepper flakes\r\nA small handful of basil leaves, most left whole, a few slivered for garnish\r\n1/4 cup olive oil\r\n12 ounces (3/4 pound) spaghetti\r\n1 tablespoon unsalted butter (optional)\r\n\r\n<strong>
180	19746	Theres only so far Stacys Pita Chips and Hummus can go. Sure, you can vary the type of hummus but in the end, it's a little too predictable. I love to have these Wontons (a.k.a "Tequeos" in Spanish) for a snack or as an appetizer platter when my friends are over. Dipped in guac or any other sauce youd like, these cheesy wontons are amazing and filling. So ditch the pita chips and introduce some South America into your life. Its anything but predictable.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time</strong>: 20 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time</strong>: 10 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 30 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings</strong>: 8\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 <em>Queso Fresco</em> pack, found at Whole Foods in the cold cheese section\r\n1 wonton dough pack, found at Whole Foods right next to the cheese\r\nVegetable oil as needed, or sunflower seed oil (do not use olive oil as substitute)\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Place as many slices of the wonton dough as you can on a baking dish or cutting board.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3438" align="aligncenter" width="995"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture15.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-3438" title="screen-capture" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture15.png" width="995" height="789" /></a> Photo by Aurelie Corinthios[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Slice the cheese into roughly 1.5 inch pieces that are about as thick as your fingers.\r\n3. Place one piece of cheese at the center of the Wonton dough.\r\n<em>Tip: You know the cheese is the right size if you have about a finger of space on the top and on the bottom. You want to make sure the dough can close over the cheese.</em>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3439" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-113.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-3439" title="screen-capture-1" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-113.png" width="1024" height="792" /></a> Photo by Aurelie Corinthios[/caption]\r\n\r\n<em></em>4. With a wet finger, line the edges of the dough so they become moist and can stick together easily.\r\n5. Fold each side over the cheese tightly, one over the other.<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-213.png"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-3440" title="screen-capture-2" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-213-1024x790.png" width="1024" height="790" /></a>6. Press the top fold down and bring in each corner. Fold the bottom in the same way. Do this for each wonton piece.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3441" align="aligncenter" width="972"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-312.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-3441" title="screen-capture-3" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-312.png" width="972" height="788" /></a> Photo by Aurelie Corinthios[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Once all your Wontons are filled with cheese and closed properly, add a tablespoon of oil to a skillet over medium-high heat. Place cheese-filled Wontons to the skillet and turn over when browning. Make sure both sides are brown and crispy.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3442" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-410.png"><img class="size-large wp-image-3442" title="screen-capture-4" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-410-1024x677.png" width="1024" height="677" /></a> Photo by Aurelie Corinthios[/caption]\r\n\r\n<em></em>8. Remove from skillet and keep warm.\r\n<em>   Tip: Place the Wontons on a plate covered with paper towel before serving to soak up excess oil.</em>\r\n<em></em>9. Repeat steps until you have a sizable batch of wontons. Remember to add more more oil to the skillet each time.\r\n10. Serve these Tequeos with guac for the perfect party platter or a delicious snack!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_3443" align="aligncenter" width="830"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-59.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-3443" title="screen-capture-5" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2012/05/screen-capture-59.png" width="830" height="791" /></a> Photo by Aurelie Corinthios[/caption]\r\n\r\n<em>Tip: Its fine to do these ahead of time. To serve the day after, drizzle with a bit of vegetable oil before heating in the microwave or oven.</em>	South American Cheese Wontons	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/south-american-cheese-wontons/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:29.959328	2014-01-14 18:55:29.959328	:</strong>\r\n1 <em>Queso Fresco</em> pack, found at Whole Foods in the cold cheese section\r\n1 wonton dough pack, found at Whole Foods right next to the cheese\r\nVegetable oil as needed, or sunflower seed oil (do not use olive oil as substitute)\r\n\r\n<strong>
181	19753	<p dir="ltr">Craving your favorite candies from your time spent studying abroad? Or perhaps youre just a candy-lover looking for something new to intrigue your taste buds. Either way, check out two new candy shops carrying imported sweets and treats,<a href="http://www.gunz.cc/Confectionery" target="_blank">GUNZ Fine European</a> and <a title="The London Candy Company" href="http://www.londoncandy.com/" target="_blank">The London Candy Company</a>.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">GUNZ, which opened in mid-September on University Place at the corner of 12th St., carries a unique selection of candies and snacks from Belgium and Austria, and all at extremely reasonable prices.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/baker_chocorice-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-3061" alt="Photo by Katherine Baker" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/10/baker_chocorice-1-1024x689.jpg" width="980" height="659" /></a> Photo by Katherine Baker[/caption]\r\n\r\nDescribed by an employee as a Crunch bar on crack, the ChocnRice bar is a customer favorite. Puffed rice cereal mixed with smooth milk chocolate gives way to a noticeably softer - and more addictive - twist on its American partner. The Schoko Bananen candies--pillowy layers of banana filling coated in chocolate--are among the other must-tries.\r\n<p dir="ltr">After GUNZ, take a quick walk to the corner of Bleecker and Morton St. in the West Village to visit The London Candy Company. Opened on August 10th, this tiny but adorably decorated store is quickly gaining popularity. The sign on the floor reads Keep Calm and Eat Candy, but with the exciting selection of snacks, it's near impossible to contain that kid-in-a-candy-store excitement.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Baker_londoncandycoexterior-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-3064" alt="Photo by Katherine Baker" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/10/Baker_londoncandycoexterior-1-1024x707.jpg" width="980" height="676" /></a> Photo by Katherine Baker[/caption]\r\n<p dir="ltr">London Candy Co. carries an unparalleled selection of British sweets, including an extensive selection of Cadbury products, European Kit Kats (think peanut butter and hazelnut flavors), as well as potato crisps in flavors like Ketchup and Beef &amp; Onion. They also serve Stumptown Coffee at fair prices and are one of only five places in the city that has Stumptown Cold Brew on tap.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">For the nostalgic, the shop also carries Crispy M&amp;Ms, a former American favorite that was discontinued in the US in 2005.If you're feeling fancy, try the Wine Gums. With the texture of Jujubes and the flavors of sweet wine, these finessed gummy candies are delightfully intriguing, and a great choice for candy and wine lovers of all ages.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/baker_winegums-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-3066" alt="Photo by Katherine Baker" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/10/baker_winegums-1-1024x682.jpg" width="980" height="652" /></a> Photo by Katherine Baker[/caption]\r\n<p dir="ltr">So put down the Reese's at Duane Reade and try something new. Hop the ponds with your taste buds at these two new candy shops.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="682"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/baker_stumptowncoffeandwinegums-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-3065" alt="Photo by Katherine Baker" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/10/baker_stumptowncoffeandwinegums-1-682x1024.jpg" width="682" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Katherine Baker[/caption]	S