ture to the saucepan.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-461" alt="Photo by Annie Madole" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10062840486_6ed0f2291d_b.jpg" width="1024" height="680" /> Photo by Annie Madole[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Stir in brown sugar and cinnamon.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-463" alt="Photo by Annie Madole" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10062917243_2c4894d830_b.jpg" width="1024" height="680" /> Photo by Annie Madole[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-464" alt="Photo by Annie Madole" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10062808555_52755cef90_b.jpg" width="1024" height="680" /> Photo by Annie Madole[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Let boil for two minutes and serve hot. Vanilla ice cream on top is optional, but undeniably preferred.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-460" alt="Photo by Annie Madole" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10062799995_7e76ac8c4b_b.jpg" width="1024" height="680" /> Photo by Annie Madole[/caption]</li>\r\n</ol>	Apples Sans Crumble	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/apples-sans-crumble/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:29.983893	2014-01-14 18:55:29.983893	:\r\n</b> cup butter\r\n4 large Honeycrisp apples  peeled, cored and sliced\r\n2 teaspoons cornstarch\r\n cup cold water\r\n cup brown sugar\r\n teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n\r\n<b>
184	19842	I get it - fall sometimes leads to pumpkin overkill. But until we can't stand the thought of another pumpkin muffin, pumpkin pie, or pumpkin spice latte  nothing beats the <em>falliness</em> of this staple ingredient. This recipe was passed down to me last year when my friend was craving her moms cookies. Not only are they fluffy with that traditional autumn spice, the icing brings them to a whole new level. Mmmmm.\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong>15 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong>20 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong>35 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong>36 cookies\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n2  cups all-purpose flour\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n1 teaspoon baking powder\r\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n teaspoon ground nutmeg\r\n teaspoon salt\r\n butter (1 stick), softened\r\n1  cups sugar\r\n1 cup pumpkin puree\r\n1 egg\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla extract\r\n1 cup chocolate chips\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Preheat oven to 350F.Lightly grease two baking sheets.</li>\r\n\t<li>In a medium bowl, combine flour, baking soda, baking powder, cinnamon, nutmeg and salt.</li>\r\n\t<li>In a large bowl, cream together butter and sugar until fluffy, about 1 minute.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-453" alt="Photo by Sarah Comerford" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10192807633_e95e418af9_b.jpg" width="1024" height="862" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Add pumpkin puree, egg and vanilla. Mix until smooth, about 1 minute.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-450" alt="Photo by Sarah Comerford" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10192619674_db9f4a0c6c_b.jpg" width="1024" height="905" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Gradually add in flour mixture, mixing on low speed, for about 2 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-451" alt="Photo by Sarah Comerford" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10192723365_68def1d8eb_b.jpg" width="1024" height="898" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Add chocolate chips (I usually add in more than 1 cup...oops.)\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-452" alt="Photo by Sarah Comerford" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10192806103_4a18c30711_b.jpg" width="1024" height="823" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Scoop dough by the tablespoon onto greased baking sheets.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-454" alt="Photo by Sarah Comerford" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10192722425_44c8cf397e_b.jpg" width="1024" height="690" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Bake 16-18 minutes, or until cookie edges are firm.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-448" alt="Photo by Sarah Comerford" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10192805173_c78dd7423e_b.jpg" width="1024" height="688" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Cool on baking sheets for 2 minutes. Move to wire rack to cool completely.</li>\r\n\t<li>Once completely cooled, drizzle glaze (recipe below) over cookies.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_449" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-449" alt="Photo by Sarah Comerford" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10192617084_3a2dc637f4_b.jpg" width="1024" height="818" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<b>Icing</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n2 cups sifted powdered sugar\r\n3 tablespoons milk\r\n1 tablespoon melted butter\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla extract\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>In a medium bowl, combine sifted powdered sugar, milk, butter and vanilla.</li>\r\n\t<li>Mix with a whisk until icing is smooth.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-455" alt="Photo by Sarah Comerford" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10192616294_4de028afd7_b.jpg" width="1024" height="932" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Once cookies have cooled completely, drizzle glaze over cookies.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-456" alt="Photo by Sarah Comerford" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10192616704_c8156c8baf_b.jpg" width="1024" height="1024" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;	Pumpkin Chocolate Chip Cookies 	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/pumpkin-chocolate-chip-cookies/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:29.985631	2014-01-14 18:55:29.985631	:</strong>\r\n2  cups all-purpose flour\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n1 teaspoon baking powder\r\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n teaspoon ground nutmeg\r\n teaspoon salt\r\n butter (1 stick), softened\r\n1  cups sugar\r\n1 cup pumpkin puree\r\n1 egg\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla extract\r\n1 cup chocolate chips\r\n\r\n<strong>
185	19853	These delicious chocolate pumpkin muffins are absurdly easy to make; their only two ingredients are a can of pumpkin and your choice of chocolate cake mix. Honestly, theyre <i>that</i> simple.While the finished product is more chocolatey as far as flavor is concerned, the pumpkin does a great deal for the texture, making these muffins fluffy, moist and indulgent.Feel free to use any cake mix you like - Ive tried this recipe with several different mixes and have yet to find one that doesnt work. That said, these muffins could easily be made gluten-free, low-carb, or even Paleo-friendly with the appropriate cake mix.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 5 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong> 15-20 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 20-25 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 12 muffins\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:\r\n</strong>1 15oz can of pumpkin\r\n1 package chocolate cake mix\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="838"]<img class=" " alt="" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5468/10124122956_0833ef2422_b.jpg" width="838" height="1024" /> Photo by Sarah Stettin[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Preheat oven to 350F.</li>\r\n\t<li>Grease a standard sized 12-cup muffin tin.</li>\r\n\t<li>Prepare cake mix as directed.</li>\r\n\t<li>Mix pumpkin and cake mix together in a medium sized bowl until well-combined.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class=" " alt="" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7440/10124129636_4616cbecc8_b.jpg" width="1024" height="680" /> Photo by Sarah Stettin[/caption]\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Spoon batter into muffin tin, filling roughly 2/3 of each cup.</li>\r\n\t<li>Bake for about 15-20 minutes, or until a toothpick can be removed cleanly from the center.</li>\r\n\t<li>Let cool, and enjoy.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5513/10123969584_5dc2d50408_b.jpg" width="1024" height="680" /> Photo by Sarah Stettin[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;	Simple Chocolate Pumpkin Muffins	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/way-easy-chocolate-pumpkin-muffins/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:29.98762	2014-01-14 18:55:29.98762	:\r\n</strong>1 15oz can of pumpkin\r\n1 package chocolate cake mix\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="838"]<img class=" " alt="" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5468/10124122956_0833ef2422_b.jpg" width="838" height="1024" /> Photo by Sarah Stettin[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>
186	19858	The leaves are falling, an autumn chill is in the air, and pumpkin spice lattes are <em>everywhere</em>. Yet while the fall festivities are in full swing on the streets of Ann Arbor, the inside of your house or apartment could probably use some extra autumn flare. A batch of these chewy, spiced cookies will satisfy that craving, leaving both your stomach and your roommates happy that fall has finally arrived.\r\n\r\n[advanced]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep Time</b>: 1 hour 10 minutes\r\n<b>Cook Time</b>: 10 minutes\r\n<b>Total Time</b>: 1 hour 20 minutes\r\n\r\n<b>Servings</b>:36 cookies\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients</b>:\r\n cup margarine, melted\r\n1 cup brown sugar\r\n1 egg\r\n cup molasses\r\n2 cups all-purpose flour\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n teaspoon salt\r\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n teaspoon ground cloves\r\n teaspoon ground ginger\r\n cup white sugar (for rolling)\r\n1 12 oz. bag white chocolate chips\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>In a medium bowl, combine melted margarine, brown sugar and 1 egg; mix until smooth.</li>\r\n\t<li>Stir in the molasses.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="840"]<a href="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10090249926_b0498ef67f_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-431" alt="Photo by Sarah Stettin" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10090249926_b0498ef67f_b.jpg" width="840" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Sarah Stettin[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>In a separate bowl, combine flour, baking soda, salt, cinnamon, cloves and ginger.</li>\r\n\t<li>Blend the dry mixture into the molasses mixture.</li>\r\n\t<li>Cover dough with plastic wrap, and chill in fridge for 1 hour.</li>\r\n\t<li>Preheat oven to 375F. Remove chilled dough from fridge and shape into walnut sized balls.</li>\r\n\t<li>Roll the dough balls through white sugar and spread evenly onto ungreased baking sheets (about 2 inches apart).\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img class="size-full wp-image-432" alt="Photo by Sarah Stettin" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10090221125_a498cbe444_b.jpg" width="1024" height="547" /> Photo by Sarah Stettin[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Bake for 8-10 minutes in preheated oven.</li>\r\n\t<li>Remove from baking sheets and cool cookies completely on paper towels.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10090300743_476a7e437e_b.jpg" width="1024" height="734" /> Photo by Sarah Stettin[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Melt white chocolate chips using a double boiler or microwave.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="649"]<img class="size-full wp-image-433" alt="Photo by Sarah Stettin" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10090219775_2ef32a0f9e_b.jpg" width="649" height="1024" /> Photo by Sarah Stettin[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>Dip  of cooled cookie into chocolate and let dry.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="823"]<a href="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10124082485_1c0a5406a7_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-437" alt="Photo by Sarah Stettin" src="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/8/2013/10/10124082485_1c0a5406a7_b.jpg" width="823" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Sarah Stettin[/caption]</li>\r\n</ol>	White Chocolate Dipped Molasses Cookies	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/white-chocolate-dipped-molasses-cookies/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:29.989203	2014-01-14 18:55:29.989203	</b>:\r\n cup margarine, melted\r\n1 cup brown sugar\r\n1 egg\r\n cup molasses\r\n2 cups all-purpose flour\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n teaspoon salt\r\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n teaspoon ground cloves\r\n teaspoon ground ginger\r\n cup white sugar (for rolling)\r\n1 12 oz. bag white chocolate chips\r\n\r\n<strong>
189	20191	Who needs the warm embrace of a loved one beneath flannel blankets on crisp fall mornings when you can pull a comforting, warm apple crisp from the microwave? These three recipes are so delicious and snuggle-worthy, and youll fall even more in love with how simple and cheap they are. Better yet, each is vegan and gluten-free. All you need to make the most of one of falls sweetest natural treats is a microwave and a few pantry staples.\r\n\r\n<b>Tip: </b>Hit up the Evanston Farmers' Market for organic, local apples for just $1 a pound, or make an afternoon of it and visit a <a title="5 Apple Orchards to Visit This Fall" href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/5-apple-orchards-visit-fall/">local apple orchard</a>. Youll leave with more apples than youll know what to do with.\r\n<h3><b>Microwave Apple Cinnamon Crisp</b></h3>\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204620713_e64b67546f_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17383" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204620713_e64b67546f_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep Time: </b>5 minutes\r\n<b>Cook Time: </b>3 minutes\r\n<b>Total Time: </b>8 minutes<b>\r\n</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Servings: </b>1\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients:</b>\r\n<i>Crumble Topping</i>\r\n2 tablespoons unsalted butter, softened (or vegan butter substitute)\r\n2 tablespoons brown sugar\r\n2 tablespoons old-fashioned rolled oats (use gluten-free if necessary)\r\n2 tablespoons all-purpose flour (use gluten-free flour if necessary)\r\n1 teaspoon cinnamon\r\nteaspoon ground nutmeg\r\nPinch of salt\r\n\r\n<i>Apple Filling</i>\r\n1 medium to large apple, diced in -inch cubes\r\ntablespoon unsalted butter (or vegan butter substitute)\r\n2 tablespoons light brown sugar, packed\r\n1 teaspoon cinnamon\r\nteaspoon ground nutmeg\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Combine all crumble topping ingredients in a small bowl with two forks until they form a mealy mixture.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204625893_bf8e53a6c7_h.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-17379" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204625893_bf8e53a6c7_h-1024x682.jpg" width="980" height="652" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. In a medium bowl or dish, microwave diced apples and butter for one minute to soften apples.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204425774_8f0bc6768a_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17381" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204425774_8f0bc6768a_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Add sugar, cinnamon and nutmeg, stirring to coat evenly. Sprinkle with crumble topping and microwave for about 2 minutes, watching carefully to make sure it doesnt overflow. Serve immediately, with whipped cream or ice cream if desired.<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204423054_d69e1ba15d_b.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-17382" alt="Apple crisp" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204423054_d69e1ba15d_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a>\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3><b>Microwave Maple-Walnut-Raisin Stuffed Apple</b></h3>\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204611013_538695fc2f_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17384" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204611013_538695fc2f_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep Time: </b>5 minutes\r\n<b>Cook Time: </b>3-5 minutes\r\n<b>Total Time: </b>8-10 minutes<b>\r\n</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Servings: </b>1\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients:\r\n</b>1 medium apple\r\ntablespoon raisins\r\ntablespoon walnuts, chopped\r\nSprinkle of cinnamon\r\n2 teaspoons maple syrup, plus more to serve\r\n\r\n<b>Directions:</b>\r\n1. In a small bowl, cover raisins and walnuts with hot water, allowing them to soak until youre ready to cook.\r\n2. Wash your apple and carefully cut a circular incision around the stem, twisting to remove the core. Scrape out remaining core, leaving about  inch at the bottom.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204522456_c293c09664_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17385" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204522456_c293c09664_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Place apple in a bowl and fill with raisins and walnuts. Sprinkle with cinnamon and maple syrup.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204417124_b5d5d323e4_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17386" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204417124_b5d5d323e4_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n<b></b>4. Microwave until apple is tender, about 3-5 minutes. Let cool for 5 minutes and, if desired, drizzle with more syrup before serving. Insides will be piping hot!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204518586_ddc453a75a_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17387" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204518586_ddc453a75a_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3><b>Easy Vegan Caramel Apples with Walnuts and Chocolate</b></h3>\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204506205_0d5ffa1fe9_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17423" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204506205_0d5ffa1fe9_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep Time: </b>3 minutes\r\n<b>Cook Time: </b>13 minutes\r\n<b>Total Time: </b>16 minutes\r\n\r\n<b>Servings: </b>1\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients:\r\n</b>1 large apple\r\n cup walnuts, finely chopped\r\n2 tablespoons vegan or regular chocolate chips, finely chopped\r\n4 tablespoons vegan (organic) granulated sugar\r\n teaspoon vanilla extract\r\n2  tablespoons coconut cream (available at Trader Joes)\r\nPinch of salt\r\n\r\n<b>Directions:</b>\r\n1. Pierce the top of the apple with a wooden stick or butter knife to act as a handle.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204517055_70e59e4f5c_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17424" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204517055_70e59e4f5c_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Combine chopped walnuts and chocolate in a small dish. Set aside.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204512385_4ce05146c5_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17425" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204512385_4ce05146c5_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. In a small pan over high heat, combine the sugar, vanilla, coconut cream and salt.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204607543_41c0724636_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17427" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204607543_41c0724636_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Continue stirring as mixture starts to bubble, letting it simmer for about 45 seconds. Reduce heat and stir for an additional minute. Turn off heat and pour mixture into a small dish. Refrigerate until sticky, or about 10 minutes. <strong>Tip: </strong>If your caramel doesn't really turn brown, it's fine  it still tastes caramel-y!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204409504_57c145d51c_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17430" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204409504_57c145d51c_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Roll apple in caramel until evenly coated, then roll in walnut-chocolate mixture to coat. Eat straight off the stick, or slice and serve!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204509215_dcf797dd42_b1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17433" alt="Photo by Maggie Gorman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10204509215_dcf797dd42_b1.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Maggie Gorman[/caption]	3 Easy Apple Desserts For One	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/3-easy-apple-desserts-for-one/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:3