199	21217	Desserts in the fall tend to all have one common theme: pumpkin. Now, I love pumpkin as much as the next guy, but I think the best part about fall desserts is not this vegetable, but the spices that often accompany it. Cinnamon, nutmeg, cloves - these are the spices of my dreams. Seriously, give me a spice cake any day of the week, and I'll love you forever. Promise.\r\n\r\nWhen I started making this dessert, I knew I wanted something warm - something easy, gooey and just a little bit decadent. I found myself at the grocery store pulling ingredients to make a very simple bread pudding using cinnamon bread and all my favorite fall spices. The best thing about bread pudding is that you can put pretty much any bread and jazz it up with chocolate, peanut butter or cinnamon chips. Try it with challah bread for a thicker bread pudding. Or, top it with a caramel or vanilla sauce to add a new dimension. Do yo' thang.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time: </strong>20 minutes<strong>\r\n</strong><strong>Cook Time: </strong>20-25 minutes<strong>\r\nTotal Time: </strong>About 45 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong>12\r\n\r\n<strong></strong><strong>Ingredients:\r\n</strong>1 loaf of cubed cinnamon raisin bread (try using challah bread for a thicker bread pudding)\r\n3 large eggs\r\n1 cup milk\r\ncup sugar\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla\r\nDash of nutmeg\r\nDash of cinnamon\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="770"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/10/IMG_0385.jpg"><img class=" " alt="IMG_0385" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/10/IMG_0385.jpg" width="770" height="577" /></a> Photo by Vinita Saggurti[/caption]\r\n\r\n<b>Directions:</b>\r\n\r\n1. Cube the bread.\r\n2. Mix together milk, eggs, sugar, vanilla, nutmeg and cinnamon.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="770"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/10/IMG_0388.jpg"><img class=" " alt