tion]\r\n\r\n4. Top with maple syrup, nut butter or fruit.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10676815664_d99dfca3d8_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18043" alt="Photo by Malia Hu" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10676815664_d99dfca3d8_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Malia Hu[/caption]	Pumpkin Protein Pancakes	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/pumpkin-protein-pancakes/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:31.19023	2014-01-14 18:55:31.19023	:</strong>\r\n<strong></strong>1 scoop vanilla protein powder\r\n cup pured pumpkin\r\n cup egg whites (approximately 2 egg whites)\r\n3 tablespoons oatmeal\r\n1 packet sweetener (I use Stevia)\r\nCinnamon or pumpkin pie spice to taste\r\n\r\n<strong>
245	23366	We all know that vegetables are "good for you," which explains why Mom was always trying new ways to sneak them onto our childhood dinner plates. Now that we're cooking on our own, we get to avoid all of that squishy, icky green stuff that we don't like any more now than we did ten years ago. But when I faced shopping on a budget, I started venturing into the produce section and realize that that picky, eight-year-old me should have just tried roasted vegetables. It's such a shame that it took 20 years for me to eat Parmesan roasted broccoli. My only reaction? "Damn! That's good!"\r\n\r\nSo, trust me on this one; Mom was right. Vegetables have a bunch of good stuff in them that will only serve your body better when Mono season rolls around. Why not go ahead and make these guys crunchy and tasty?\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong>10 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong>20 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong>30 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong>4 side dishes or 2 main dishes\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 zucchini squash\r\n1 broccoli crown\r\n6 baby red potatoes\r\n1 egg\r\n3 tablespoons olive oil\r\n1 teaspoon rosemary\r\n1/2 cup shredded Parmesan cheese\r\n1/4 cup bread crumbs\r\nSalt, pepper to taste\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Preheat the oven to 425F. Take out a large baking sheet, cutting board, and a couple of bowls. Clear your unfinished homework off of the counter.\r\n2. Cut off the ends of the zucchini and slice the remaining middle into 1/4 inch (or thinner) discs.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23373" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23373" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-2.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Dump pieces into a bowl and drizzle with a tablespoon of olive oil. Mix to cover all pieces.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23374" align="alignnone" width="768"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-3.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23374" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-3.jpg" width="768" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Crack an egg into a bowl and whisk.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23375" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-4.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23375" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-4.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Place 1/4 cup of Parmesan cheese, 1/4 cup of bread crumbs, a bit of salt and a dash of pepper in a separate bowl. Mix the dry ingredients.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23376" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-5.1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23376" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-5.1.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23377" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-5.2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23377" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-5.2.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Dip each zucchini slice in the egg and then into the Parmesan. Place coated slices onto the baking sheet.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23378" align="alignnone" width="768"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-6.1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23378" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-6.1.jpg" width="768" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23379" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-6.2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23379" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-6.2.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23380" align="alignnone" width="768"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-6.3.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23380" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-6.3.jpg" width="768" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Cut spears off the stalk of broccoli in bite-sized pieces.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23381" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-7.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23381" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-7.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. Place broccoli spears in a bowl and drizzle with a tablespoon of olive oil. Mix to cover all pieces and place on baking sheet.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23382" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-8.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23382" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-8.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23383" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-8.2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23383" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-8.2.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n9. Quarter baby red potatoes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23384" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-9.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23384" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-9.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n10. Place a teaspoon of rosemary in a bowl. Move the potato quarters to the bowl and drizzle with a tablespoon of olive oil. Mix to cover all pieces and place on baking sheet.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23385" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-10.1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23385" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-10.1.jpg" width="800" height="600" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23386" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-10.2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23386" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-10.2.jpg" width="800" height="600" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23387" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-10.3.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23387" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-10.3.jpg" width="800" height="600" /></a> Photo by Paige Pulaski[/caption]\r\n\r\n11. Place baking sheet in the oven.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_23388" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-11.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-23388" alt="Photo by Paige Pulaski" src="http://spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Step-11.jpg" width="1024" hei