256	23832	The holiday season is quickly approaching, which means that it is time to dust off those cookie sheets and start baking!\r\n\r\nWhile everybody enjoys a good chocolate chip cookie or sugar cookie, what people really want during the holiday season is a cookie with a kick that will keep them warm as the chill of winter inches closer. The only solution: snickerdoodles.\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep Time:</b> 30 minutes\r\n<b>Cook Time:</b> 30 minutes\r\n<b>Total Time:</b> 60 minutes\r\n\r\n<b>Makes:</b> 36 cookies<b></b>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_180" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a style="font-size: 13px;" href="http://princeton.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/11/cookie.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-180" alt="" src="http://princeton.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/11/cookie-1024x685.jpg" width="980" height="655" /></a> Photo by Lisa Gong[/caption]\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients:</b>\r\n\r\n1 cup butter (unsalted)\r\n1 1/2 cup sugar\r\n2 large eggs\r\n2 3/4 cup flour\r\n2 teaspoon cream of tartar\r\n1/4 teaspoon salt\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla (extract)\r\n2 tablespoon sugar\r\n2 tablespoon cinnamon\r\n\r\n<b>What you need:</b> 2 large bowls, 1 small bowl, 1+ 9x13 baking sheet, cooling rack (optional).\r\n\r\n<b>Directions</b>\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Preheat oven to 350F and let butter soften in large bowl.</li>\r\n\t<li>Mix butter and sugar in large bowl.</li>\r\n\t<li>Beat in eggs one at a time.</li>\r\n\t<li>Combine dry ingredients (flour, cream of tartar, salt) in a second bowl.</li>\r\n\t<li>Blend dry ingredients into butter mixture.</li>\r\n\t<li>Mix vanilla into dough.</li>\r\n\t<li>Chill dough and ungreased cookie sheet(s) for 10 minutes.</li>\r\n\t<li>While dough chills, mix 2 tbs. sugar and 2 tbs. cinnamon in small bowl.</li>\r\n\t<li>Scoop 1 inch (diameter) balls of dough into sugar-cinnamon mixture and roll until satisfactorily coated.</li>\r\n\t<li>Place dough on chilled ungreased cookie sheet and bake for 11-12 minutes.</li>\r\n\t<li>Remove from pan immediately and cool for 5-10 minutes.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<b>Tips</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>All ingredients (and equipment) can be purchased at Walmart via the Saturday Shopper bus route.</li>\r\n\t<li>If time is short, microwave the butter for 20 seconds to soften it.</li>\r\n\t<li>If an additional spice kick is desired, mix 1 tablespoon of cinnamon evenly into the dough before chilling.</li>\r\n\t<li>Sugar cookies can be made by baking the dough without coating it in the sugar-cinnamon mixture.</li>\r\n\t<li>Cookies are fully baked when they are light-brown.</li>\r\n</ul>	Chewy Snickerdoodles	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/chewy-snickerdoodles/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:31.376086	2014-01-14 18:55:31.376086	:</b>\r\n\r\n1 cup butter (unsalted)\r\n1 1/2 cup sugar\r\n2 large eggs\r\n2 3/4 cup flour\r\n2 teaspoon cream of tartar\r\n1/4 teaspoon salt\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla (extract)\r\n2 tablespoon sugar\r\n2 tablespoon cinnamon\r\n\r\n<b>What you need:</b> 2 large bowls, 1 small bowl, 1+ 9x13 baking sheet, cooling rack (optional).\r\n\r\n<b>
257	23880	With Thanksgiving coming up, its hard to resist all the delicious sweets and remain faithful to one's commitment to eating healthier. As a person with a serious sweet tooth, desserts are always the downfall to my healthy eating goals.However, we dont have to always sacrifice the enjoyment of delicious sweets for health reasons. Here are four variations of brownies, all of which do not use any oil, butter, or eggs! Try them out, adjust the amount of sugar/honey to your liking and enjoy a guilt-free dessert.\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong>Applesauce Brownies (with a pumpkin addition)</strong>\r\n<strong></strong><strong>Prep Time: </strong>15 minutes\r\n<strong> Cook Time: </strong>20-30 minutes\r\n<strong> Total Time: </strong>35-60 minutes\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong>12\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>:\r\n\r\n1 cup whole wheat flour\r\n cup brown sugar\r\nA couple of squirts of honey or agave or maple syrup\r\n1 teaspoon baking powder\r\n2 Hershey sized bars of melted dark chocolate\r\nA pinch of salt\r\n cup of unsweetened applesauce\r\n cup of soy milk or low fat milk\r\nIf you want more chocolaty flavor, add  cup of cocoa powder If you want a pumpkin addition, add 2 tablespoons of pumpkin butter\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Preheat the oven to 350F. Oil your pan so that the brownie will be able to slide off the pan (itll make cleaning your dishes a lot easier!)</li>\r\n\t<li>Melt the chocolate on low heat. Constantly stir it so it doesnt burn or get stuck to the pan.</li>\r\n\t<li>Place all the dry ingredients together in the bowl of melted chocolate: flour, sugar, baking powder, cocoa powder, salt. Whisk it nice and well.</li>\r\n\t<li>Yum, the color is looking great! Now add the wet ingredients to make a smooth brownie mix. Add honey/agave/or maple syrup, applesauce, milk, and some pumpkin butter if youd like.[row][/row]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="224"]<a href="http://princeton.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/11/2013-11-03-02.11.08.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-132 " alt="" src="http://princeton.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/11/2013-11-03-02.11.08-224x300.jpg" width="224" height="300" /></a> Photo by Margaret Wang[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>WHISK WHISK WHISK.</li>\r\n\t<li>Put it in the oven for around 20-30 minutes, depending on what kind of texture you want. If you want a gooey brownie, Id go for 20 minutes. A great way to check is to put a toothpick in the center. If theres still bits of the brownie stuck to the toothpick, that means it is still undercooked.[row][/row]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="224"]<a href="http://princeton.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/11/2013-11-03-02.43.51.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-131 " alt="" src="http://princeton.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/11/2013-11-03-02.43.51-224x300.jpg" width="224" height="300" /></a> Photo by Margaret Wang[/caption]</li>\r\n\t<li>I add hemp seeds for additional nutrients like Thiamin, Phosphorus, and Manganese. Enjoy![row][/row]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_133" align="aligncenter" width="224"]<a href="http://princeton.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/11/2013-11-03-02.47.49.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-133 " alt="" src="http://princeton.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/11/2013-11-03-02.47.49-224x300.jpg" width="224" height="300" /></a> Photo by Margaret Wang[/caption]</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Recipe variations:</strong> <strong>Sweet potato or pumpkin brownies</strong> Do the same thing as above, except instead of applesauce, use  cup of pureed pumpkins OR sweet potato.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="342"]<img alt="" src="http://i1054.photobucket.com/albums/s498/cookiesandcups/pumpkinbrownies_zps3ab85807.jpg" width="342" height="478" /> Pumpkin Browniesfrom cookiesandcups.com[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>Avocado brownies (my favorite!)</strong> This is absolutely my favorite variation of the brownie. You will achieve the soft, fudgy texture of a brownie using a ripe avocado. It sounds weird, but trust me, its delicious! To cover up the taste of the avocado, I would use a little bit more cocoa powder. Instead of  cup of applesauce, use 1 cup of mashed avocados.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="293"]<img alt="" src="http://s23.postimg.org/4lyaapfxn/Untitled2.png" width="293" height="293" /> Photo by Margaret Wang[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>Black bean or chickpea brownies</strong> Ive heard that black beans and chickpeas are also great additions to brownies and blondies. This will be my next experiment. I havent tried this yet, but <a href="http://minimalistbaker.com/vegan-gluten-free-black-bean-brownies/">minimalistbaker.com</a> details a great recipe with mouth-watering pictures for the black bean brownies.	Healthy Desserts for the Sweet Tooth	http://spoonuniversity.com/?post_type=recipe&#038;p=23880	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:31.392538	2014-01-14 18:55:31.392538	</strong>:\r\n\r\n1 cup whole wheat flour\r\n cup brown sugar\r\nA couple of squirts of honey or agave or maple syrup\r\n1 teaspoon baking powder\r\n2 Hershey sized bars of melted dark chocolate\r\nA pinch of salt\r\n cup of unsweetened applesauce\r\n cup of soy milk or low fat milk\r\nIf you want more chocolaty flavor, add  cup of cocoa powder If you want a pumpkin addition, add 2 tablespoons of pumpkin butter\r\n\r\n<strong>
259	24160	The candy first to disappear in my house isalways Reeses Peanut Butter Cups; I bought a big bag of pumpkin shaped ones that were eaten within a day. So instead of continuing tobuy more, I decided to make these no-bake homemade peanut butter cups.They willfulfill your peanut butter and chocolate cravingswhile keepingyour secret candy stash fully stocked throughout the season.\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong>10 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong>40 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 50 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings</strong>: 36 peanut butter cups\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>:\r\n1 cup creamy peanut butter\r\n1/4 cup unsalted butter\r\n1/4 teaspoon salt\r\n1 cup powdered sugar\r\n4 cups milk chocolate chips (two 11.5 oz. bags)\r\n1/4 cup vegetable shortening\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions</strong>:\r\n1. Line mini-muffin tins with paper liners and set aside.\r\n2. In a microwave-safe bowl, melt peanut butter, butter, and salt in 30-second increments.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="IMG_7113" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2890/10862430685_3a37e42a08_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Alex Weiner[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="IMG_7087" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2834/10862434745_12b75f43f1_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Alex Weiner[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Slowly stir in powdered sugar until smooth.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="IMG_7117" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3821/10862574694_14c129860e_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Alex Weiner[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. In a microwave-safe bowl, melt chocolate chips and shortening in 30-second increments, until completely melted.Be sure to stir after each increment.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2824/10749698784_89139da8e6_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Spoon a tablespoon of melted chocolate into the bottom of each lined muffin cup.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="IMG_7091" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7293/10862578514_1e66015b6d_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Alex Weiner[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Refrigerate for about 20 minutes, until chocolate is hard.\r\n7. Spoon a teaspoon of the peanut butter mixture on top of chocolate.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="683"]<img alt="IMG_7118" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7338/10862474316_71baca06e2_b.jpg" width="683" height="1024" /> Photo by Alex Weiner[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. Spoon more melted chocolate on top, enough to fully cover peanut butter (if necessary pop chocolate back into microwave to re-melt).\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="IMG_7124" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5492/10862428425_d66af358e6_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Alex Weiner[/caption]\r\n\r\n9. Refrigerate for 20 minutes, until chocolate is hard. Store in freezer or refrigerator until ready to serve.	DIY Peanut Butter Cups	http://spoonuniversity.com/?post_type=recipe&#038;p=24160	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:31.417715	2014-01-14 18:55:31.417715	</strong>:\r\n1 cup creamy peanut butter\r\n1/4 cup unsalted butter\r\n1/4 teaspoon salt\r\n1 cup powdered sugar\r\n4 cups milk chocolate chips (two 11.5 oz. bags)\r\n1/4 cup vegetable shortening\r\n\r\n<strong>
260	24165	My roommate and I like hummus. <em>A lot</em>. It's creamy, smooth, filling....and if we really wanted to, we would easily go through 4+ containers a week. We use it as a spread on toast, lathered on wraps, or use it as a dip for almost anything (awesome way to down your daily servings of veggies). But a 16oz hummus usually costs around 4-5 bucks at the store. So this is a sneaky way we create the same thing in our little apartment - and it costs less than$1.80.\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong> Total time:</strong>5 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong>6\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:\r\n</strong>1 15-ounce can garbanzo beans, rinsed\r\n1/4 cup olive oil\r\nJuice from 1 lemon, or 2 tablespoons lemon juice\r\n1 clove garlic\r\n1/2 teaspoon paprika\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<img alt="" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5498/10768077973_7cd4d75f04_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /> Photo by Parisa Soraya[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:\r\n</strong>1. In a food processor or high speed blender, pure all ingredients with a pinch of salt until smooth and creamy. You can add 1-2 tablespoons water to get your desired consistency.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<img alt="" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2846/10767870386_c5a5328635_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /> Photo by Parisa Soraya[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Transfer to a bowl and drizzle with olive oil and paprika before serving.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="534"]<img alt="" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2867/10767808715_a0f654c19e_c.jpg" width="534" height="800" /> Photo by Parisa Soraya[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Serve with bread, crackers, or sliced veggies.Perfect on its own or as party or game day food. If storing, cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate for 3-5 days.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sweet Potato Chipotle Hummus" href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/recipe/sweet-potato-chipotle-hummus-2/" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2812/10767907444_6c4a9f5a75_c.jpg" width="800" height="561" /></a> Photo by Parisa Soraya[/caption]\r\n\r\nLooking for some variation? Experiment with different spices, add in roasted red pepper, or use more/less garlic. You can also make<a title="Sweet Potato Chipotle Hummus" href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/recipe/sweet-potato-chipotle-hummus-2/" target="_blank">Sweet Potato Chipotle Hummus</a>- or if you are feeling adventurous, try your hand at<a title="Peanut Butter Hummus" href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/recipe/peanut-butter-hummus/" target="_blank">Peanut Butter Hummus</a>.	Hummus: 5 ingredients, 5 minutes	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/hummus/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:31.419842	2014-01-14 18:55:31.419842	:\r\n</strong>1 15-ounce can garbanzo beans, rinsed\r\n1/4 cup olive oil\r\nJuice from 1 lemon, or 2 tablespoons lemon juice\r\n1 clove garlic\r\n1/2 teaspoon paprika\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<img alt="" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5498/10768077973_7cd4d75f04_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /> Photo by Parisa Soraya[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>
261	24209	Regular tomatoes are great, but theyre pretty common. I can find normal tomatoes in almost any sandwich, salad, pasta, pizza  but<em>sun-dried</em>tomatoes are much more elusive. Their exotic flavor immediately stands out in any dish. Now, these guys may be pretty fancy, but dont think that they only belong in $10+ entrees at classy restaurants. Thanks to the jar of 'California Sun-Dry Sun-Dried Julienne Cut Tomatoes' that I found at Wegmans, I've recently discovered how easy it is to incorporate sun-dried tomatoes into basic recipes for a distinct savory kick. Case-in-point: the sun-dried tomato melt and sun-dried tomato brie 'dip.'\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Sun-dried Tomato Melt</strong>\r\n\r\nEssentially a twist on the classic tomato-mozzarella sandwich, this melt only requires four ingredients and under 10 minutes.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong>2-3 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong>5-6 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time: </strong>9minutes maximum\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings</strong>: Makes one open-faced melt\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 slice basic sandwich bread (I used Wegmans Soft-Crusted Multigrain)\r\n1 slice mozzarella cheese\r\n1.5-3 tablespoons sun-dried tomatoes, according to preference\r\n1 pat (roughly one teaspoon) unsalted butter\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Spoon tomatoes onto the slice of bread. The bread can be toasted or toasted based on preference and toaster accessibility.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich Prep by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717283456/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich Prep" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2818/10717283456_bb73e345b6_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Top sun-dried tomatoes with a slice of mozzarella.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich Prep by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717194065/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich Prep" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7384/10717194065_08c46bdc3c_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Melt the pat of butter in a small saucepan over low heat.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Melting Butter by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717193645/"><img class=" " alt="Melting Butter" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3779/10717193645_edd8922c9d_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Slide the open-face sandwich into the pan, then cover the pan with a lid. Allow the bread to brown for 4-5 minutes, uncovering it once or twice to slide it around the pan with a spatula.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich in the Pan by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717193555/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich in the Pan" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2845/10717193555_2ee1080648_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Using two spatulas or similar flat utensils, flip the sandwich onto the cheese side. To do this, slide one spatula under the bread while the other covers the cheese and then flip as quickly as possible. Allow it to melt,<em>uncovered</em>, for 10-30 seconds (longer = melt-ier but messier).\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich Flip by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10721397815/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich Flip" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2878/10721397815_a65905a054_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Turn off the stove and flip the sandwich the same way as before, making sure that the lower spatula is between the cheese and the pan,<em>not</em>the cheese and the tomatoes. If the flip gets messy, use the spatula to spread the tomatoes and cheese across the sandwich while they're still in their melty, moldable state.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich Finished by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717282806/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Sandwich Finished" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3779/10717282806_145e1e2b6f_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Sun-dried Tomato &amp; Brie Dip</strong>\r\nYou've probably been wondering why 'dip' is in quotes. Fact is, this simple combination of brie and sun-dried tomatoes doesn't have the creamy or saucy consistency of most dips, but it goes so well with chips or crackers that I insist on presenting it as such.\r\n\r\nSlightly adapted from <a href="http://www.pastryaffair.com/blog/2012/3/18/sun-dried-tomato-basil-brie-spread.html">Pastry Affair</a>\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong>15-20 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong>0minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time: </strong>15-20minutes maximum\r\n<strong>Servings</strong>: Makes one small, about 7-ounce bowl of dip.\r\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>:\r\n6 ounces brie cheese (I used Wegmans Medium, Buttery Camembert)\r\n5 tablespoons sun-dried tomatoes\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions</strong>\r\n1. Using a sharp knife, carve as much of the rind - the thin, white casing around the soft cheese - off of the cheese as possible without cutting out too much of the cheese itself. The rind is perfectly edible, but removing it allows the cheese to lose its shape and be mashed with the tomatoes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Brie Prep by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717540446/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Brie Prep" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7338/10717540446_992c62ac0f_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Brie Prep by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717523244/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Brie Prep" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3685/10717523244_1c15c8cd34_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Spoon the sun-dried tomatoes into the bowl and mash them with the cheese. Tip: even if you bought pre-cut tomatoes, chop them further before adding; I didn't and quickly realized that mixing would've been much easier if I had.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Adding Tomato by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717540206/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Adding Tomato" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2819/10717540206_ae715a5027_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Mixing by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717446315/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Mixing" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2845/10717446315_bb4987453e_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\nVoila! It may not look great, but who judges food by looks instead of taste?\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Almost Finished by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10717446175/"><img class=" " alt="Sun-dried Tomato Spread Almost Finished" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2869/10717446175_1c7640e2e2_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Agnes Chen[/caption]	Sun-dried Tomato Samplers	http://spoonuniversity.com/?recipe=sun-dried-tomato-one-sandwich-one-dip-one-heck-ingredient	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:31.424502	2014-01-14 18:55:31.424502	:</strong>\r\n1 slice basic sandwich bread (I used Wegmans Soft-Crusted Multigrain)\r\n1 slice mozzarella cheese\r\n1.5-3 tablespoons sun-dried tomatoes, according to preference\r\n1 pat (roughly one teaspoon) unsalted butter\r\n\r\n<strong>
262	24242	Right around the first frost of the year, sweet potatoes come out of the ground and onto our dinner plates. This year, get creative and dress up the potato with one of the 5 suggestions below.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep Time: </b>Under 2 minutes\r\n<b>Cook Time:</b> 5 minutes\r\n<b>Total Time: </b>7 minutes\r\n\r\n<b>Servings:</b> 1\r\n\r\n<b>Directions:</b>\r\n\r\nWash the potato. Using a fork, poke holes all over. Microwave on full power for about 5 minutes (or, if your microwave has it, press the potato button). Once the potato is cooked, careful cut it in half and go crazy!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582474024_541ddd76d3_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-435" alt="Photo by Kristen Yang" src="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582474024_541ddd76d3_c.jpg" width="800" height="562" /></a> Photo by Kristen Yang[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Brown sugar and salt</strong>\r\n\r\nFor this one, use less sugar than salt. They are sweet potatoes, after all. Mash the inside of the potato to combine.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582383486_56cd837d3f_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-436" alt="Photo by Kristen Yang" src="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582383486_56cd837d3f_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Kristen Yang[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>2. Plain and simple</strong>\r\n\r\nHot, fresh, mashed sweet potatoes are like a call to home after a long day of classes.Take a few bites of the skin to get the most out of the <a href="http://www.sweetpotato.org/content/nutritional-info">sweet potato's nutrients</a>.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_437" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582354475_860fa44359_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-437" alt="Photo by Kristen Yang" src="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582354475_860fa44359_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Kristen Yang[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>3. Add a pinch of paprika and salt</strong>\r\n\r\nYou can't go wrong with both a sweet and spicy potato.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582626503_7200655518_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-434" alt="Photo by Kristen Yang" src="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582626503_7200655518_c.jpg" width="800" height="573" /></a> Photo by Kristen Yang[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>4. The traditional mashed potato</strong>\r\n\r\nMaybe lay off of the sour cream, but a little butter and salt have never hurt.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582352285_2176154c49_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-433" alt="Photo by Kristen Yang" src="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582352285_2176154c49_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Kristen Yang[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>5. Marshmallows on top</strong>\r\n\r\nFor those Thanksgiving-style casserole goodness cravings, this hits the spot. Once the potato is cooked and cut open, drop in a few mini marshmallows. Microwave for 20 seconds and mash.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582355485_e2e1345ab1_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-439" alt="Photo by Kristen Yang" src="http://uiuc.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2013/11/10582355485_e2e1345ab1_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Kristen Yang[/caption]	5 Easy Ways to Eat the Ultimate 