271	24692	Since sweet potatoes are considered healthier than their classic white counterpart, I try to incorporate them into my dinners throughout the fall. I love making (and eating) mashed sweet potatoes, baked sweet potatoes and even sweet potato chips. But whenever I want a challenge, I make my grandmothers sweet potato <a title="In Defense of Pasta" href="http://michigan.spoonuniversity.com/food-thought/defense-pasta/">gnocchi</a> recipe. Try your hand at this more difficult recipe for Thanksgiving and wow your friends and family with this savory and filling side dish.\r\n\r\n[advanced]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 45 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong> 45 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 1 hour and 30 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 4 dinner portions\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n2 lbs sweet potatoes (usually 2 or 3  I used 2 )\r\n1 egg yolk\r\n1  - 2 cups unbleached all-purpose flour\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Preheat over to 425F. Cut sweet potatoes in half lengthwise and drizzle with extra-virgin olive oil, salt and pepper.\r\n2. Place on a rimmed baking sheet, cut side down and bake until tender for about 30-35 minutes (you'll know it's done if you can stick a fork in the potato and pull it out potato-free).\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3759/10812911054_303538e5b7_b.jpg" width="1024" height="934" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Allow sweet potatoes to cool, then scoop potato flesh into a large mixing bowl. Smash with a potato ricer, potato masher or big fork, until smooth.\r\n4. Stir in egg yolk.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2837/10812781356_ea03fbc7ae_b.jpg" width="1024" height="903" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Mix in flour,  cup at a time, adding more flour until dough is damp but not sticking to your hand.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" 