ds/sites/7/2013/11/pralines-cream-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Becky Hughes[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Microwave on high for 5 minutes.\r\n\r\n3. Take the bowl out of the microwave and stir the mixture several times.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines-stir-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4157" alt="Photo by Becky Hughes" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines-stir-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Becky Hughes[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Microwave on high for an additional 4 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines-microwave-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4155" alt="Photo by Becky Hughes" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines-microwave-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Becky Hughes[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Let the mixture rest for one minute.\r\n6. Stir in the vanilla extract and continue stirring for an additional minute.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines-stir1-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4159" alt="Photo by Becky Hughes" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines-stir1-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Becky Hughes[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Drop by the teaspoonful onto a cookie tray or buttered wax paper.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines5-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4163" alt="Photo by Becky Hughes" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines5-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Becky Hughes[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="678"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines1-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4160" alt="Photo by Becky Hughes" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/pralines1-1-678x1024.jpg" width="678" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Becky Hughes[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/praline-bowl1-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4150" alt="Photo by Becky Hughes" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/praline-bowl1-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Becky Hughes[/caption]	Microwave Pralines 	http://spoonuniversity.com/?post_type=recipe&#038;p=25187	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:31.865087	2014-01-14 18:55:31.865087	:\r\n</b>1  cups dark brown sugar\r\n2/3 cup heavy cream\r\n1/8 teaspoon salt\r\n1  cups pecan halves\r\n1 tablespoon margarine or butter\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla extract\r\n\r\n<b>
290	25231	Its that time of year again. The leaves are changing color, the air is getting crisper, and all food products are starting to taste suspiciously like pumpkin or apple. This is the perfect recipe for jumping on the autumnal bandwagon. Keep in mind that donuts are not for the faint of heart. But they are worth it none the less. Set aside an afternoon, muster up a little patience and a spirit of adventure and set forth into your kitchen. When you bite into the piping hot, cozy doughiness of a fresh apple cider donut you sure will be glad you did.\r\n\r\n[advanced]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 90 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time</strong>: 15 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 105 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 16-18 donuts\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0439-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4091" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0439-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients\r\n</b>1 cup apple cider\r\n1 small-medium apple, chopped\r\n3 1/2 cups flour + additional for working dough\r\n2 teaspoon baking powder\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg\r\n1/2 teaspoon salt\r\n4 tablespoons (1/2 stick) of butter\r\n1 cup granulated sugar\r\n2 eggs\r\n1/4 cup buttermilk\r\nVegetable oil or shortening for frying\r\nAdditional sugar and cinnamon for topping (optional)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Directions\r\n</b>1. Heat the apple cider in a small saucepan over medium heat. Let it simmer for 25 minutes, uncovered. After 15 minutes, add the chopped apples. Let them stew in the cider, becoming soft and browned. Let the mixture cool before using.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0442-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4092" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0442-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. In a small bowl mix together the flour, baking soda, baking powder, cinnamon, nutmeg, and salt.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0493-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4099" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0493-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Now in a separate bowl, beat the butter and sugar together with an electric mixer (or the paddle attachment of a stand mixer). Add the eggs one by one and beat until smooth.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0504-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4100" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0504-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0512-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4101" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0512-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Stir in the apple cider mixture and buttermilk. When it's well combined, stir in the flour until the dough just comes together.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0528-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4102" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0528-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0532-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4103" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0532-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Turn the dough out onto the baking sheet, sprinkling generously with flour. Using your hands, flatten it on the sheet until it is about 1/2 inch thick. If your dough is obnoxiously sticking to your hands, dont lose hope. Continuously add more flour to the dough as you flatten.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0535-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4104" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0535-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0540-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4106" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0540-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Put the dough in the freezer to chill for 20 minutes. We understand that many of us have tiny freezers and this will be difficult. Persevere on.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0538-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4105" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0538-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. After the dough chills, it's time to shape the doughnuts. The easiest way to do this is to use a cup as you would a cookie cutter. A 3 inch diameter glass works well. Transfer your rounds to a new baking sheet with parchment paper. Use a knife to cut out small holes in the middle.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0547-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4107" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0547-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. At the end of this process you will be left with scraps from the cutting process and the doughnut holes. Re-flatten these (working with flour as needed) and shape them into donuts as well. Refrigerate all shaped doughnuts for 30 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0550-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4108" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0550-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0557-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4109" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0557-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n9. Now you are ready to fry your donuts. This is the fun part, where you get to feel like a cooking wizard. It is best to use vegetable shortening for this, as it will produce less oily end products, but feel free to substitute with vegetable oil. Heat the oil in a deep sided pan until it measures about 350 degrees on a candy thermometer. If you dont have a thermometer, no worries. Stick the end of a wooden spoon into your oil. If bubbles start to form around the wood and float up, your oil is hot enough.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0562-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4111" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0562-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n10. Use a spatula to slide the donuts 3 at a time into the hot oil. Fry for about one minute on the first side, until golden brown. Fry for 30 seconds-1 minute on the second side. Remove doughnuts with the spatula and transfer to a plate covered with paper towels.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0572-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4112" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0572-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0578-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4114" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0578-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n11. In a small bowl mix together equal parts cinnamon and sugar. Let the donuts cool for a minute or two before rolling, while still hot, in your cinnamon-sugar mix.\r\n\r\n12. Eat these donuts fresh. And eat many of them. Happy Fall!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0591-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4116" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0591-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n<em>Adapted from <a href="http://smittenkitchen.com/blog/2009/10/apple-cider-doughnuts/">Smitten Kitchen</a></em>	Apple Cider Doughnuts	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/apple-cider-donuts-2/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:31.904759	2014-01-14 18:55:31.904759	\r\n</b>1 cup apple cider\r\n1 small-medium apple, chopped\r\n3 1/2 cups flour + additional for working dough\r\n2 teaspoon baking powder\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg\r\n1/2 teaspoon salt\r\n4 tablespoons (1/2 stick) of butter\r\n1 cup granulated sugar\r\n2 eggs\r\n1/4 cup buttermilk\r\nVegetable oil or shortening for frying\r\nAdditional sugar and cinnamon for topping (optional)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>
291	25287	When fall comes around, you want to use apples in as many ways possible while theyre deliciously in season. This panini features a classic ham and cheddar combo, enhanced with the special addition of sweet apples. I used Honeycrisp apples in this version, but a more tart apple like a Granny Smith will work as well. When choosing a deli ham, look for varieties that aren't sweetened with honey or maple.\r\n<b></b>\r\n[easy]\r\n<b></b>\r\n<b>Prep Time: </b>5 min\r\n<b>Cook Time: </b>10 min\r\n<b>Total Time: </b>15 min\r\n\r\n<b>Servings: </b>1\r\n<b></b>\r\n<b>Ingredients:</b>\r\n6-8 slices of deli ham (add more if you want a heftier sandwich)\r\nCheddar cheese, sliced\r\napple, cored and thinly sliced\r\n2 slices bread\r\n tablespoon butter\r\n\r\n<b>Directions:</b>\r\n1. Heat panini press to approximately 375F.\r\n2. Melt butter in a frying pan.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865577194_566ee805be_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18460" alt="Photo by Justin Shannin" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865577194_566ee805be_b.jpg" width="1024" height="609" /></a> Photo by Justin Shannin[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Place ham slices in the pan when butter is melted. Cook until browned (about 4 minutes), flipping them over halfway through.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865577244_4737894fca_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18461" alt="Photo by Justin Shannin" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865577244_4737894fca_b.jpg" width="1024" height="609" /></a> Photo by Justin Shannin[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. While the ham cooks, thinly slice your apple. The thin slices will release some of the apples juices to keep your panini from getting soggy.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865426875_20c062c191_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18459" alt="Photo by Justin Shannin" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865426875_20c062c191_b.jpg" width="1024" height="685" /></a> Photo by Justin Shannin[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Layer fried ham, cheddar and apple slices onto your bread. Top with other slice of bread.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865577084_0f500e5e90_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18458" alt="Photo by Justin Shannin" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865577084_0f500e5e90_b.jpg" width="1024" height="519" /></a> Photo by Justin Shannin[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Press the sandwich in the panini maker for 3-5 minutes, until bread starts to brown.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_18457" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865576964_f9ae2b58d7_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18457" alt="Photo by Justin Shannin" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/10/10865576964_f9ae2b58d7_b.jpg" width="1024" height="675" /></a> Photo by Justin Shannin[/caption]	Fried Ham, Cheddar and Apple Panini	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/fried-ham-cheddar-apple-panini/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:31.937065	2014-01-14 18:55:31.937065	:</b>\r\n6-8 slices of deli ham (add more if you want a heftier sandwich)\r\nCheddar cheese, sliced\r\napple, cored and thinly sliced\r\n2 slices bread\r\n tablespoon butter\r\n\r\n<b>
292	25340	Its that time of year again. The leaves are changing color, the air is getting crisper, and all food products are starting to taste suspiciously like pumpkin or apple. This is the perfect recipe for jumping on the autumnal bandwagon. Keep in mind that donuts are not for the faint of heart. But they are worth it none the less. Set aside an afternoon, muster up a little patience and a spirit of adventure and set forth into your kitchen. When you bite into the piping hot, cozy doughiness of a fresh apple cider donut you sure will be glad you did.\r\n\r\n[advanced]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 90 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time</strong>: 15 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 105 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 16-18 donuts\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0439-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4091" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0439-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients\r\n</b>1 cup apple cider\r\n1 small-medium apple, chopped\r\n3 1/2 cups flour + additional for working dough\r\n2 teaspoon baking powder\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg\r\n1/2 teaspoon salt\r\n4 tablespoons (1/2 stick) of butter\r\n1 cup granulated sugar\r\n2 eggs\r\n1/4 cup buttermilk\r\nVegetable oil or shortening for frying\r\nAdditional sugar and cinnamon for topping (optional)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Directions\r\n</b>1. Heat the apple cider in a small saucepan over medium heat. Let it simmer for 25 minutes, uncovered. After 15 minutes, add the chopped apples. Let them stew in the cider, becoming soft and browned. Let the mixture cool before using.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0442-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4092" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0442-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. In a small bowl mix together the flour, baking soda, baking powder, cinnamon, nutmeg, and salt.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0493-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4099" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0493-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Now in a separate bowl, beat the butter and sugar together with an electric mixer (or the paddle attachment of a stand mixer). Add the eggs one by one and beat until smooth.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0504-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4100" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0504-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0512-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4101" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0512-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Stir in the apple cider mixture and buttermilk. When it's well combined, stir in the flour until the dough just comes together.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0528-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4102" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0528-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0532-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4103" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0532-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Turn the dough out onto the baking sheet, sprinkling generously with flour. Using your hands, flatten it on the sheet until it is about 1/2 inch thick. If your dough is obnoxiously sticking to your hands, dont lose hope. Continuously add more flour to the dough as you flatten.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0535-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4104" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0535-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0540-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4106" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0540-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Put the dough in the freezer to chill for 20 minutes. We understand that many of us have tiny freezers and this will be difficult. Persevere on.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0538-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4105" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0538-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. After the dough chills, it's time to shape the doughnuts. The easiest way to do this is to use a cup as you would a cookie cutter. A 3 inch diameter glass works well. Transfer your rounds to a new baking sheet with parchment paper. Use a knife to cut out small holes in the middle.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0547-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4107" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0547-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. At the end of this process you will be left with scraps from the cutting process and the doughnut holes. Re-flatten these (working with flour as needed) and shape them into donuts as well. Refrigerate all shaped doughnuts for 30 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0550-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4108" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0550-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0557-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4109" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0557-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n9. Now you are ready to fry your donuts. This is the fun part, where you get to feel like a cooking wizard. It is best to use vegetable shortening for this, as it will produce less oily end products, but feel free to substitute with vegetable oil. Heat the oil in a deep sided pan until it measures about 350 degrees on a candy thermometer. If you dont have a thermometer, no worries. Stick the end of a wooden spoon into your oil. If bubbles start to form around the wood and float up, your oil is hot enough.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0562-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4111" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0562-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n10. Use a spatula to slide the donuts 3 at a time into the hot oil. Fry for about one minute on the first side, until golden brown. Fry for 30 seconds-1 minute on the second side. Remove doughnuts with the spatula and transfer to a plate covered with paper towels.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0572-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4112" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0572-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0578-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4114" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0578-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n11. In a small bowl mix together equal parts cinnamon and sugar. Let the donuts cool for a minute or two before rolling, while still hot, in your cinnamon-sugar mix.\r\n\r\n12. Eat these donuts fresh. And eat many of them. Happy Fall!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0591-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4116" alt="Photo by Margaret Weinberg" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/DSC_0591-1-1024x678.jpg" width="980" height="648" /></a> Photo by Margaret Weinberg[/caption]\r\n\r\n<em>Adapted from <a href="http://smittenkitchen.com/blog/2009/10/apple-cider-doughnuts/">Smitten Kitchen</a></em>	Apple Cider Doughnuts	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/apple-cider-donuts-3/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:32.005916	2014-01-14 18:55:32.005916	\r\n</b>1 cup apple cider\r\n1 small-medium apple, chopped\r\n3 1/2 cups flour + additional for working dough\r\n2 teaspoon baking powder\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg\r\n1/2 teaspoon salt\r\n4 tablespoons (1/2 stick) of butter\r\n1 cup granulated sugar\r\n2 eggs\r\n1/4 cup buttermilk\r\nVegetable oil or shortening for frying\r\nAdditional sugar and cinnamon for topping (optional)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>
293	25373	<p style="text-align: left">The weather is getting colder and classes are getting busier. Comfort is much needed and Nutella, in any form, is sure to deliver. Nutella can be put on nearly anything, such as cookies, bread, fruit, crepes and yogurt. But when made into a hot and milky substance, the satisfaction level rockets. This simple and easy recipe takes under three minutes and warms your belly and soul with every sip, so throw that textbook aside and grab a mug.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a title="IMG_6877 by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10891178376/"><img alt="IMG_6877" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3775/10891178376_731c664b6d_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Parsa Lotfi[/caption]\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 30 seconds\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong> 2 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 3 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 1\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 spoonful of Nutella\r\n3 pieces of a chocolate bar\r\n1 cup milk\r\nPinch of salt\r\nDash of cinnamon (or more)\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Put the Nutella and chocolate bar in a microwavable mug with enough milk to barely cover the Nutella.\r\n2. Microwave for about 30 seconds and stir. Keep microwaving until the chocolate is completely melted into the milk.\r\n3. Add the rest of the milk and microwave for another 30 seconds, or until hot. Keep an eye on it, as the milk may begin to bubble.\r\n4. Add a small pinch of salt and a dash of cinnamon and stir. Top with whipped cream, more chocolate, or any other toppings you desire literally go nuts, chopped hazelnuts perhaps?\r\n5. Enjoy while hot.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="534"]<a title="IMG_6904 by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10890985875/"><img alt="IMG_6904" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5510/10890985875_cc4d2cfa85_c.jpg" width="534" height="800" /></a> Photo by Parsa Lotfi[/caption]	Nutella Hot Chocolate	http://spoonuniversity.com/?post_type=recipe&#038;p=25373	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:32.030417	2014-01-14 18:55:32.030417	:</strong>\r\n1 spoonful of Nutella\r\n3 pieces of a chocolate bar\r\n1 cup milk\r\nPinch of salt\r\nDash of cinnamon (or more)\r\n\r\n<strong>
294	25378	Getting a surprise jar of pumpkin butter from my parents, in addition to the two boxes of gingersnaps that Id requested, was definitely a highlight of parents weekend. I mean, seeing my parents after over a month was pretty cool  but, seriously, <i>pumpkin butter!</i>It's an extremely smooth jam thats all kinds of wonderful. I stumbled upon these <a href="http://www.bloggingoverthyme.com/2013/10/22/pumpkin-butter-pecan-scones/">pumpkin butter pecan scones</a> while perusing Blogging over Thymes recipes and was instantly intrigued. I don't own a mixer nor the desire to buy half a dozen ingredients to make dough so I went for the cop-out method of store-bought dough to make rolls. Then, before adding cloves and brown sugar to my shopping list, my eyes settled on my remaining box of gingersnaps and the resulting fall flavor only required me to buy two ingredients and left my taste-testing photographers and I lost for words.\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time</strong>: 20 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time</strong>: 15 minutes (+ 5 minutes cooling time)\r\n<strong>Total Time</strong>: 40 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings</strong>: 8 single-roll servings (realistically, 4 servings - you won't eat<em>just one</em>)\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>:\r\n1 dough sheet (I used a Pillsbury Crescent Seamless Dough Sheet; baking times will vary by brand)\r\n1/3 cup pumpkin butter\r\n cup chopped pecans\r\n cup *crushed gingersnaps\r\n\r\n*Put the cookies in a plastic bag, pushing as much of air out as possible before sealing it. Use something sturdy with a broad base, like a measuring cup or mug, or a rolling pin to grind the cookies into crumbs.\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions</strong>:\r\n1. Preheat oven to 375F.\r\n2. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Unroll the dough  mine came out to about 8x11 inches  on the paper and cut in half non-lengthwise, as pictured below.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Pumpkin Butter Pecan Gingersnap Roll Prep by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10847456135/"><img alt="Pumpkin Butter Pecan Gingersnap Roll Prep" src="http://farm6.staticflickr.com/5507/10847456135_20b7c1dff6_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Dividing the <sup>1</sup>/<sub>3</sub> cup quantity equally between the two halves, spread the pumpkin butter across the dough, leaving a -inch margin from the edges.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Pumpkin Butter Pecan Gingersnap Roll Prep by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10847604104/"><img alt="Pumpkin Butter Pecan Gingersnap Roll Prep" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7443/10847604104_b37a81692e_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Pumpkin Butter Pecan Gingersnap Roll Prep by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10847520626/"><img alt="Pumpkin Butter Pecan Gingersnap Roll Prep" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7378/10847520626_17bde7ed3f_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Sprinkle the chopped pecans across the pumpkin butter of both halves.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Pumpkin Butter Pecan Gingersnap Roll Prep by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/10847456175/"><img alt="Pumpkin Butter Pecan Gingersnap Roll Prep" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7329/10847456175_502f438023_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Anthony Wan[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Coat each half with gingersnap crumbs.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a title="Pumpkin Butter Pecan Gingersnap Roll Prep by University of Rochester SPOON, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/104802925@N07/1