299	25548	The name is pretty self-explanatory: egg + avocado = the best 2-ingredient breakfast since milk and cereal. The egg is cooked in the empty hole where the avocado pit used to be, so it's easy to eat and fun to make. Plus, 6 grams of protein and 5 grams of monounsaturated will help keep you full before lunchtime or after a workout.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time: </strong>5 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time: </strong>15 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time: </strong>20 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 1\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 egg\r\n1/2 avocado\r\nSalt and pepper as desired\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Preheat the oven to 400F.\r\n2. Cut the avocado in half (save the other half for another Eggocado) and take the pit out.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/10934072154_a02002aeed_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-420" alt="Photo by Libby Perold" src="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/10934072154_a02002aeed_b.jpg" width="1024" height="819" /></a> Photo by Libby Perold[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Cut a thin slice off the underside of the avocado, so that it sits flat on your cutting board.\r\n4. Crack the egg in a bowl. Pour as much as you want into the hollow of the avocado. If the hole is too small and you want to use the whole egg, scrape out some of the avocado to create more space.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/10933991266_e0bf22dec4_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-423" alt="Photo by Libby Perold" src="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/10933991266_e0bf22dec4_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Libby Perold[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="683"]<a href="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/egg1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-421" alt="Photo by Libby Perold" src="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/egg1.jpg" width="683" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Libby Perold[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Place your uncooked Eggocado onto a skillet or pan and bake for 15 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/10933981206_83d48b578c_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-425" alt="Photo by Libby Perold" src="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/10933981206_83d48b578c_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Libby Perold[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Remove from the oven and season with salt and pepper, dill or sriracha.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="683"]<a href="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/10933916905_012141deee_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-426" alt="Photo by Libby Perold" src="http://washu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2013/11/10933916905_012141deee_b.jpg" width="683" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Libby Perold[/caption]	The Eggocado	http://spoonuniversity.com/?post_type=recipe&#038;p=25548	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:32.133342	2014-01-14 18:55:32.133342	:</strong>\r\n1 egg\r\n1/2 avocado\r\nSalt and pepper as desired\r\n\r\n<strong>
