76" /></a> Photo by Christine Pritula[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a title="Bacon Apple Brie Sandwich by WashU Spoon, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/106291453@N07/10838365606/"><img alt="Bacon Apple Brie Sandwich" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3695/10838365606_c7c4d9dbc9_b.jpg" width="1024" height="576" /></a> Photo by Christine Pritula[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Butter one side of each piece of bread.\r\n5. Place bread, butter-side down, on frying pan over medium heat.\r\n6. Lay Brie slices flat on one piece of bread and then layer apple slices on top of Brie.\r\n7. Spread honey mustard on second piece of bread and close sandwich by placing bread on apple slices.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a title="Bacon Apple Brie Sandwich by WashU Spoon, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/106291453@N07/10838641593/"><img alt="Bacon Apple Brie Sandwich" src="http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2884/10838641593_6961b12b52_b.jpg" width="1024" height="576" /></a> Photo by Christine Pritula[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. Grill for 4 minutes on each side.\r\n9. Remove sandwich from pan. Open sandwich and add spinach and bacon.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a title="Bacon Apple Brie Sandwich by WashU Spoon, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/106291453@N07/10838364336/"><img alt="Bacon Apple Brie Sandwich" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3683/10838364336_6f63a0798a_b.jpg" width="1024" height="576" /></a> Photo by Christine Pritula[/caption]\r\n\r\n10. Close sandwich and serve warm.	Bacon, Apple and Brie Sandwich	http://spoonuniversity.com/?post_type=recipe&#038;p=25549	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:32.135173	2014-01-14 18:55:32.135173	</b>:\r\n2-4 bacon strips\r\n sweet apple, sliced\r\n2 ounces Brie cheese\r\n2 slices of lightly buttered bread\r\n cup spinach\r\n2 teaspoons honey mustard\r\n\r\n<b>
302	25572	We probably all grew up eating applesauce. I, for one, was often shipped off to school with my little snack pack of Motts. Motts is okay, but it is basically the jealous little sibling of homemade applesauce, which is superior in every way. Do yourself a favor and make this. It takes so little effort and I give you permission to eat it at all times of the day and to not share.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep time: </b>15 minutes\r\n<b>Cook time: </b>20 minutes\r\n<b>Total time:</b> 35 minutes\r\n\r\n<b>Servings</b>: About 5 cups\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients:</b>\r\n\r\n<b></b>3 lb bag McIntosh apples\r\n- cup brown sugar*\r\n1-2 teaspoons cinnamon*\r\n1 tablespoon lemon juice\r\n\r\n*Youll notice I put ranges here. Applesauce is very customizable, so add sugar and cinnamon to taste. Additionally, feel free to use a different sweetener, and add/omit spices.\r\n\r\n<b>Directions:</b>\r\n\r\n1. Peel and core the apples. Slice into  inch thick slices.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="770"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/11/10907700504_29d1e6d9e4_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1267" alt="Photo by " src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/11/10907700504_29d1e6d9e4_b.jpg" width="770" height="500" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Place apple slices in a pot with sugar, lemon, and cinnamon. Add a dash of water. Stir.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="770"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/11/10907588466_51f2d19e62_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1268" alt="Photo by Marykate Surrette" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/11/10907588466_51f2d19e62_b.jpg" width="770" height="500" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n3.Cover the pot and cook over medium-low heat for about 20 minutes, or until the apples break down and become very soft.\r\n\r\n