313	25839	As Thanksgiving break approaches, it's hard to find a simple way to tackle the dozens of Facebook event invitations (as if Reading Week lasts a year), travel plans and the haunting of unfinished homework. One of the most annoying parts about Thanksgiving and winter break, however, is the battle between holiday parties and the need to use up everything in your fridge before rushing off to O'hare. It might be tempting to try and impress your friends with ambitious recipe for a holiday party, but why not try this easy applesauce for a dorm potluck or family gathering? You just need a dozen apples and cinnamon, meaning you won't need to scour Pinterest for what to do with leftovers. Also, with no added sugar, it's a healthy addition to the season of treat yo' self. Lastly, if you're celebrating Thanksgivukkah this year, this applesauce is a seasonal and traditional way to complement potato latkes.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 15 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong> 45 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 1 hour\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 12\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n12 apples, rinsed and dried\r\n2 tablespoons ground cinnamon\r\n2 cups water\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Cut and core apples, and chop into about 1-inch pieces.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10967896005_48148c0766_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18627" alt="10967896005_48148c0766_b" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10967896005_48148c0766_b.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Kendra Valkema[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10967894825_efc705fc9f_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18626" alt="10967894825_efc705fc9f_b" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10967894825_efc705fc9f_b.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Kendra Valkema[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Add apples, water and cinnamon to a large soup pot. Cook over medium-low heat until apples are mushy and water is incorporated into applesauce, about 45 minutes.\r\n3. Turn off heat. Use a potato masher to roughly mash apples into a chunky applesauce. You can also use a mixer (which will create an even chunkier sauce) or a food processor or blender (both of which will create a smoother sauce).\r\n4. Transfer to a serving bowl and serve immediately, or store in the fridge for up to a week.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_18625" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10967894035_4540561a8b_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18625" alt="Photo by" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10967894035_4540561a8b_b.jpg" width="1024" height="768" /></a> Photo by Kendra Valkema[/caption]	2 Ingredient Applesauce	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/2-ingredient-applesauce/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:32.213912	2014-01-14 18:55:32.213912	:</strong>\r\n12 apples, rinsed and dried\r\n2 tablespoons ground cinnamon\r\n2 cups water\r\n\r\n<strong>
314	25853	As the last football game of the season approaches, there is no time like the present to make Jell-O shots that showcase your Northwestern spirit. These strawberry lemonade Jell-O shots have it all: they're purple, sweet and portable, making them the perfect snack for the shuttle to Ryan Field (or inside the stadium if you're really sneaky).\r\n\r\nThe Jell-O shot recipe is simple: you only need a package of Jell-O, water or fruit juice, the alcohol of your choice and, of course,<a href="http://www.amazon.com/Plastic-Jello-Shot-Lids--125ct/dp/B004Y4Z7NS/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1384295556&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=jello+shot">plastic Jell-O shot cups</a>. Just how much alcohol you use depends on what <a href="http://www.streetdirectory.com/food_editorials/beverages/alcoholic_drinks/jello_shot_making_guide_and_jello_shot_recipe.html">proof</a> it is.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep Time</b>: 15 minutes\r\n<b>Cooling Time</b>: 4 hours\r\n<b>Total Time</b>: 4 hours 15 minutes\r\n\r\n<b>Servings</b>: 27 2-ounce shots\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients:</b>\r\n1 6-ounce package of strawberry Jell-O\r\n1  cups vodka, plus up to  cup Absolut Citron if the vodka has a lower proof\r\n2 cups lemonade\r\n1 cup water\r\nBlue food coloring\r\nNon-stick cooking spray\r\nJell-O shot cups\r\n\r\n<b>Directions</b>:\r\n1. Stir together vodka and  cup of water in a cup. Place in freezer to chill.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857676953_e7b9174454_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18377" alt="Photo by Kirby Barth" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857676953_e7b9174454_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Kirby Barth[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Bring the lemonade and  cup of water to a boil. Meanwhile, pour the Jell-O powder into a small bowl.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857485884_5b67719c12_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18375" alt="Photo by Kirby Barth" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857485884_5b67719c12_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Kirby Barth[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Once the lemonade mixture has come to a boil, pour it over the powder and stir until all of the powder is completely dissolved.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857322885_33e923aa82_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18376" alt="Photo by Kirby Barth" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857322885_33e923aa82_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Kirby Barth[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Stir in the chilled vodka and water mixture.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857381236_3134c4d963_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18371" alt="Photo by Kirby Barth" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857381236_3134c4d963_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Kirby Barth[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Slowly add drops of blue food coloring in as you stir until you reach a perfect Wildcat purple, about 6 drops.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857665793_58658e7e1e_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18372" alt="Photo by Kirby Barth" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857665793_58658e7e1e_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Kirby Barth[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Lightly spray the inside of the Jell-O cups with the cooking spray. (This will help the shots slide out of the cups easier come game time.)\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857664533_c20e651716_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18373" alt="Photo by Kirby Barth" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857664533_c20e651716_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Kirby Barth[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Ladle the liquid Jell-O into the cups. (My cups are 2 ounces, so I use a  measuring cup, which fills each cup almost all the way.) Put lids on if you have them, and carefully place the Jell-O cups in the fridge until set, at least 4 hours.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_18368" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857663463_cf263dd849_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18368" alt="Photo by Kirby Barth" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857663463_cf263dd849_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Kirby Barth[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857469134_beeaea755f_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-18369" alt="Photo by Kirby Barth" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/10857469134_beeaea755f_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /></a> Photo by Kirby Barth[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. Keep the Jell-O shots refrigerated until the last second, otherwise they begin to melt. Serve cold and enjoy wisely!	Wildcat Jell-O Shots	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/wildcat-jell-o-shots/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:32.223672	2014-01-14 18:55:32.223672	:</b>\r\n1 6-ounce package of strawberry Jell-O\r\n1  cups vodka, plus up to  cup Absolut Citron if the vodka has a lower proof\r\n2 cups lemonade\r\n1 cup water\r\nBlue food coloring\r\nNon-stick cooking spray\r\nJell-O shot cups\r\n\r\n<b>
322	26266	When we <a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/2013/11/qa-zach-oliver/">interviewed</a> NU football player Zack Oliver for our <a href="http://issuu.com/nuspoonmag/docs/_spoon_fall_2013_online">fall magazine</a>, we discovered he is much more than a college quarterback he is quite the cook. Raised in Baton Rouge, La., he loves the southern comfort food he grew up eating. Here is Zack's recipe for one of his signature dishes and a cajun favorite: jambalaya. Just one bite and maybe you'll be throwing like a Big Ten quarterback.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<b>Prep Time:</b>20 minutes\r\n<b>Cook Time:</b>25 minutes\r\n<b>Total Time:</b>45 minutes\r\n\r\n<b>Servings:</b>4 people (2 football players?)\r\n\r\n<b>Ingredients:</b>\r\n1 pound beef sausage, sliced\r\n1 pound chicken, cooked\r\n1 can French onion soup\r\n2 cups chicken broth\r\n1 cup beef broth\r\nOak Grove Smokehouse Cajun Dirty Rice\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3374.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-18758" alt="Photo by Daniel Schuleman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3374-1024x682.jpg" width="980" height="652" /></a> Photo by Daniel Schuleman[/caption]\r\n\r\n<b>Directions:</b>\r\n<b></b>1. Brown sausage in a pan over medium heat, then drain grease.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3368.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-18762" alt="Photo by Daniel Schuleman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3368-1024x682.jpg" width="980" height="652" /></a> Photo by Daniel Schuleman[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Pull cooked chicken into bite-sized pieces using your hands or two forks.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="682"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3364.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-18761" alt="Studio Day 4-3364" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3364-682x1024.jpg" width="682" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Daniel Schuleman[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Add soup and both broths into a large pot, and bring to a boil.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3366.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-18763" alt="Photo by Daniel Schuleman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3366-1024x682.jpg" width="980" height="652" /></a> Photo by Daniel Schuleman[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Add cooked sausage and pulled chicken to soup-broth mixture.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3379.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-18764" alt="Photo by Daniel Schuleman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3379-1024x682.jpg" width="980" height="652" /></a> Photo by Daniel Schuleman[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Add the rice.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="682"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3383.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-18765" alt="" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3383-682x1024.jpg" width="682" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Daniel Schuleman[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Cover and simmer for 25 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3389.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-18766" alt="Photo by Daniel Schuleman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3389-1024x682.jpg" width="980" height="652" /></a> Photo by Daniel Schuleman[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Remove from heat, and let sit for a few minutes prior to serving.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="682"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3404.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-18757" alt="Photo by Daniel Schuleman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3404-682x1024.jpg" width="682" height="1024" /></a> Photo by Daniel Schuleman[/caption]	Zack Oliver's Jambalaya	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/zack-olivers-jambalaya/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:32.469937	2014-01-14 18:55:32.469937	:</b>\r\n1 pound beef sausage, sliced\r\n1 pound chicken, cooked\r\n1 can French onion soup\r\n2 cups chicken broth\r\n1 cup beef broth\r\nOak Grove Smokehouse Cajun Dirty Rice\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3374.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-18758" alt="Photo by Daniel Schuleman" src="http://nu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2013/11/Studio-Day-4-3374-1024x682.jpg" width="980" height="652" /></a> Photo by Daniel Schuleman[/caption]\r\n\r\n<b>
