318	26042	Its starting to get chilly outside. Extra layers of sweaters and snuggly scarves arent the only way to face the colda steaming bowl of soup is one of the best ways to warm up. Caldo Verde is a traditional Portuguese soup with potatoes, greens and sausage. Its crazy good even in the summertime, but during the cold months it is particularly satisfying. This recipe for my grandmothers version is easy enough for any college cook to manage.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 10 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong> 50 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 1 hour\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 6\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:\r\n</strong>4 large potatoes\r\n1  teaspoons salt\r\n8 cups of water\r\n cups olive oil\r\n teaspoon pepper\r\n6 ounces chorizo sausage\r\n pound kale, shredded\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\n1.Peel the potatoes. Cut them into 1/4-inch thick round slices.Dont worry about getting all the skin off when you peel the potatoes. Skin will give the soup a little extra flavor and texture.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-1-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4305" alt="Photo by Tallie Gabriel" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-1-1-1024x683.jpg" width="980" height="653" /></a> Photo by Tallie Gabriel[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Cook the potatoes in a large pot with salt and water until they are tender, about 30 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-2-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4307" alt="Photo by Tallie Gabriel" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-2-1-1024x683.jpg" width="980" height="653" /></a> Photo by Tallie Gabriel[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Mash the potatoes into bite-sized pieces. If you dont have a potato masher, its also easy to do this with a spoon.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-four-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4313" alt="Photo by Tallie Gabriel" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-four-1-1024x683.jpg" width="980" height="653" /></a> Photo by Tallie Gabriel[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Stir in the olive oil and pepper.\r\n\r\n5. Prick holes the sausages with a fork, and add them to the pot.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-3.2-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4309" alt="Photo by Tallie Gabriel" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-3.2-1-1024x549.jpg" width="980" height="525" /></a> Photo by Tallie Gabriel[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Let the mixture simmer for about 15 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-4-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4310" alt="Photo by Tallie Gabriel" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-4-1-1024x683.jpg" width="980" height="653" /></a> Photo by Tallie Gabriel[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Remove the sausages. Cut them into bite-sized slices then return them to the pot.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-5-1.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-4311" alt="Photo by Tallie Gabriel" src="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2013/11/step-5-1-1024x683.jpg" width="980" height="653" /></a> Photo by Tallie Gabriel[/caption]\r\n\r\n8.Add the kale and let simmer for 3 to 4 more minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="980"]<a href="http://nyu.spoonuniversity.com/w