/a> Photo by Emily Kurtz[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. In a separate bowl, blend butter, brown sugar, and sugar until light yellow and fluffy.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="640"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183771713_ced7ab4fe7_z.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1681" alt="11183771713_ced7ab4fe7_z" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183771713_ced7ab4fe7_z.jpg" width="640" height="480" /></a> Photo by Emily Kurtz[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Add eggs and vanilla to the butter mixture.\r\n5. Slowly add in the dry ingredients until the mixture appear doughy.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="640"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183601505_e951f50b02_z.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1674" alt="11183601505_e951f50b02_z" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183601505_e951f50b02_z.jpg" width="640" height="480" /></a> Photo by Emily Kurtz[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Mash sprinkles, oreos, M&amp;M's, and pretzels into the dough.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="640"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183659224_0e5b680884_z.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1680" alt="11183659224_0e5b680884_z" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183659224_0e5b680884_z.jpg" width="640" height="480" /></a> Photo by Emily Kurtz[/caption]\r\n\r\n7. Put two inch balls of the dough onto baking sheets (don't spray if the pan is nonstick).\r\n8. Cook for 9-11 minutes. Watch them closely so that they don't over cook!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="640"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183662384_a16bc3fdb1_z.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1682" alt="11183662384_a16bc3fdb1_z" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183662384_a16bc3fdb1_z.jpg" width="640" height="480" /></a> Photo by Emily Kurtz[/caption]\r\n\r\n9. Let them cool before warming your tummy with this delicious, flavorful, gooey delight.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="640"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183649416_65b4e0651f_z1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1683" alt="11183649416_65b4e0651f_z" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11183649416_65b4e0651f_z1.jpg" width="640" height="480" /></a> Photo by Emily Kurtz[/caption]	Day 8: Festive Funfetti Cookies	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/day-8-festive-funfetti-cookies/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:33.354881	2014-01-14 18:55:33.354881	:</b>\r\n\r\n12 tablespoons unsalted butter\r\n1 cup brown sugar\r\ncup granulated sugar\r\n2 eggs\r\n2 tablespoons vanilla extract\r\n2 cups flour\r\nteaspoon baking soda\r\nPinch of salt\r\ncup sprinkles\r\ncup crushed Oreos\r\ncup red and green M&amp;M's\r\ncup crushed pretzels\r\n\r\n<b>
360	28196	Throughout the month of December, my parents house smells of freshly baked gingerbread. The iconic holiday gingerbread men fill up the cookie jar throughout the holiday season. The cookies are delicious any way you choose: plain, topped with icing or decorated with mini M&amp;Ms, and the dough can be cut into whatever shape your friends or family prefer  just keep the shapes PG for family parties...\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 1 hour and 15 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong> 8-12 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> 1 hour and 30 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 3-4 dozen gingerbread men (depending on what size you make them)\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:\r\n</strong>1/2 cup butter or margarine\r\n1/2 cup brown sugar\r\n1/2 cup, 2 tablespoons molasses\r\n1 egg\r\n1 1/2 teaspoons cinnamon\r\n1/2 teaspoon ground ginger\r\n1/2 teaspoon salt\r\n1/2 teaspoon baking soda\r\n3 cups flour\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. In a large bowl, cream butter and brown sugar until light and fluffy.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3684/11199350574_4008fe00fc_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]\r\n\r\n2. Blend in the molasses and egg.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3786/11199359886_7157291f6c_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Add cinnamon, ground ginger, salt and baking soda and mix well.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7371/11199360616_450f79ed4c_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Slowly add in flour. Stir until flour is fully mixed.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3801/11199479103_d64f67924e_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Wrap dough in saran wrap. Refrigerate at least an hour or up to 2 days.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3681/11199524273_4d79ebe37c_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. When ready to bake gingerbread, preheat oven to 350F. On a lightly floured surface, roll out the dough to a 1/8-1/4 inch thickness. Using a cookie cutter, cut out gingerbread men (or any holiday shape you want).\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3715/11199487373_5dc6fd0ff3_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. Bake for 8-12 minutes (depending on thickness and shape size), until light brown.\r\n9. Transfer to wire rack and let cool for decorating.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="1024"]<img alt="" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7313/11199509673_2eea239732_b.jpg" width="1024" height="683" /> Photo by Sarah Comerford[/caption]	Gingerbread Cookies	http://spoonuniversity.com/?post_type=recipe&#038;p=28196	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:33.506727	2014-01-14 18:55:33.506727	:\r\n</strong>1/2 cup butter or margarine\r\n1/2 cup brown sugar\r\n1/2 cup, 2 tablespoons molasses\r\n1 egg\r\n1 1/2 teaspoons cinnamon\r\n1/2 teaspoon ground ginger\r\n1/2 teaspoon salt\r\n1/2 teaspoon baking soda\r\n3 cups flour\r\n\r\n<strong>
