371	28830	Cant get enough of the rich, buttery flavor of Greek Christmas cookies? Heres another recipe to indulge courtesy of our friend Natalia, aka <a href="http://www.thegreekglutton.com/">The Greek Glutton</a>. Melomakarona are made with honey, cinnamon and cloves, are soaked in a honey-orange syrup and topped with brown sugar and walnuts. Dont be intimidated by the long list of ingredients, the steps are simple and the results divine!\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 40 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong> 30 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time</strong>: around 70 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> around 30\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients for the Syrup:</strong>\r\n1 <b></b>cups sugar\r\n2 cups water\r\n cup honey\r\n cinnamon stick (ground cinnamon works too)\r\n1 strips of orange peel\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients for the Dough:</strong>\r\n3 cups flour\r\n cup olive oil\r\n stick unsalted butter (room temperature)\r\n1 tablespoon honey\r\n cup sugar\r\n cups orange juice\r\n2 teaspoons. ground cinnamon\r\n teaspoon ground cloves\r\n teaspoon baking soda\r\n1  teaspoon baking powder\r\nZest from  an orange\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients for the Topping:</strong>\r\n cup walnuts, finely ground\r\ncup brown sugar\r\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\r\n teaspoon ground cloves\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n1. Preheat your oven to 300F.\r\n2. In a pot bring the sugar, water, honey, orange peel and cinnamon to a boil. Reduce the heat and simmer for 10 minutes. Allow it to cool and place it in the fridge.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11334338334_879dc45df8_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1841" alt="Photo by Natalia Alexander" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11334338334_879dc45df8_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Natalia Alexander[/caption]\r\n\r\n3. Meanwhile, combine the sugar, olive oil and butter in a large bowl until fully incorporated. Add the orange juice, cinnamon, cloves, baking soda, baking powder, and orange zest and mix. Gradually add the flour until the dough becomes soft, but not sticky.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11334315116_0184e46db5_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1842" alt="Photo by Natalia Alexander" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11334315116_0184e46db5_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Natalia Alexander[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Form each cookie into a small oval and place on the parchment paper. Bake for 30 minutes.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11334608906_a47a9f285b_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1843" alt="Photo by Natalia Alexander" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11334608906_a47a9f285b_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Natalia Alexander[/caption]\r\n\r\n5. Meanwhile, make the topping by combining the walnuts, brown sugar, cinnamon and cloves.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11334315636_cd0c199126_c.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1844" alt="Photo by Natalia Alexander" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11334315636_cd0c199126_c.jpg" width="800" height="534" /></a> Photo by Natalia Alexander[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Once the cookies are slightly cooled, soak them in the cold syrup (1/3 of the batch at a time) for 20 minutes. Stir occasionally to coat all the sides.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="aligncenter" width="800"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/