388	29706	Christmas cookies are really fun to look at and really fun to make. These cookies are no exception, where  once again  chocolate meets peppermint. You'll love these cookies during the holidays and dont be afraid to get creative and customize your decorating.\r\n\r\n<em>Recipe adapted from <a title="yummy mummy kitchen" href="http://www.yummymummykitchen.com/2013/11/chocolate-christmas-drop-cookies.html">yummy mummy kitchen</a></em>\r\n\r\n[medium]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep Time:</strong> 10 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook Time:</strong> 10 minutes\r\n<strong>Total Time:</strong> About 20 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong>About 2 dozen cookies\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n\r\n cup of flour\r\n cup of cocoa powder\r\n1 stick of butter\r\n2 eggs\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla\r\n1 teaspoon baking powder\r\n cup of brown sugar\r\nPinch of salt\r\n1 bag of Dove peppermint bark chocolates\r\n1 container of white frosting\r\nRed and green crushed candy canes\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="700"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532052466_4a51a371af_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1977" alt="Photo by Marykate Surette" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532052466_4a51a371af_b.jpg" width="700" height="468" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Preheat oven to 325F.\r\n\r\n2. Spray a baking sheet very lightly with non-stick baking spray.\r\n\r\n3. Divide the bag of chocolates in half and set one half aside for later. Add the remaining half into a bowl along with the butter. Melt in three 30 second intervals in the microwave until smooth.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="700"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532044964_4555cc6979_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1978" alt="Photo by Marykate Surette" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532044964_4555cc6979_b.jpg" width="700" height="468" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n4. Mix the flour, cocoa powder, baking powder and a pinch of salt in another bowl.\r\n\r\n5. In a separate bowl, beat the eggs and sugar until light yellow.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="700"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532073486_a79df2be9c_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1981" alt="Photo by Marykate Surette" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532073486_a79df2be9c_b.jpg" width="700" height="468" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. Add the flour mixture and the melted chocolate mixture into the bowl with the beaten eggs and mix well. Beat until the dry ingredients are fully incorporated.\r\n\r\n7. Chop the rest of the Dove chocolates.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="700"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532084334_2b19fb4b75_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1975" alt="Photo by Marykate Surette" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532084334_2b19fb4b75_b.jpg" width="700" height="468" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n8. Fold the chocolate pieces into the batter.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="700"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532046465_d9cdeba804_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1974" alt="Photo by Marykate Surette" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532046465_d9cdeba804_b.jpg" width="700" height="468" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n9. Drop tablespoons of batter on the baking sheet.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="700"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532046745_eef8c1ba3f_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1980" alt="Photo by Marykate Surette" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532046745_eef8c1ba3f_b.jpg" width="700" height="468" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n10. Bake for about 10 minutes.Remove from the oven and let completely cool.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="700"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532126406_01128a5aba_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1979" alt="Photo by Marykate Surette" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532126406_01128a5aba_b.jpg" width="700" height="468" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n11. Using a knife or a mini spatula spread the white frosting in an even layer on each cookie. Sprinkle the crushed candy cane on top.	Peppermint Christmas Cookies	http://spoonuniversity.com/recipe/peppermint-christmas-cookies/	\N	2014-01-14 18:55:34.306195	2014-01-14 18:55:34.306195	:</strong>\r\n\r\n cup of flour\r\n cup of cocoa powder\r\n1 stick of butter\r\n2 eggs\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla\r\n1 teaspoon baking powder\r\n cup of brown sugar\r\nPinch of salt\r\n1 bag of Dove peppermint bark chocolates\r\n1 container of white frosting\r\nRed and green crushed candy canes\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_" align="alignnone" width="700"]<a href="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532052466_4a51a371af_b.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1977" alt="Photo by Marykate Surette" src="http://upenn.spoonuniversity.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2013/12/11532052466_4a51a371af_b.jpg" width="700" height="468" /></a> Photo by Marykate Surette[/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>
389	29742	Red velvet cake is a staple dessert. It's commonly mistaken for chocolate cake, but its flavors are more layered than your usual cocoa sweet. This recipe is particularly special because of its simplicity, moistness and rich taste. Easily dressed in any flavor of icing, it also pairs well with fruits, like raspberries, that give it extra texture. This dessert will make you fight for the last morsel. Make it for occasions ranging from a casual baking party to a sophisticated dinner.\r\n\r\n[easy]\r\n\r\n<strong>Prep time:</strong> 5-10 minutes\r\n<strong>Cook time:</strong> 25-30 minutes\r\n<strong>Total time:</strong> 30-40 minutes\r\n<strong>Servings:</strong> 10-12\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n\r\n2  cups cake flour\r\n2 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa powder\r\n1 teaspoon baking powder\r\n1 teaspoon baking soda\r\n teaspoon salt\r\n1 cup buttermilk\r\n1 tablespoon red food coloring\r\n1 teaspoon distilled white vinegar\r\n1 teaspoon vanilla extract\r\n1  cups sugar\r\n cup (1 stick) unsalted butter at room temperature\r\n2 large eggs\r\n1 container of store-bought icing (vanilla, chocolate, or cream cheese would work)\r\n1 container of fresh raspberries (or fruit of your choice) for topping\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Preheat oven to 350F. Butter two 9-inch circular pans and coat them lightly with all-purpose flour.\r\n2. Mix flour, cocoa powder, baking powder, baking soda, salt, buttermilk, food coloring, vinegar, and vanilla in small bowl and set aside.\r\n3. Gently beat sugar and butter with a mixer.\r\n4. Gradually add flour mixture (from step 2) to the butter and sugar until well blended. Add eggs 1 at a time, beating well after each addition.\r\n5. Divide batter between prepared pans.\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignnone" width="770"]<a title="Edited 3 by uchi.spoonuniversity, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/106796684@N05/11254415143/"><img alt="Edited 3" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7335/11254415143